{"title_page": "Lobini H1", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=November 2011}}\n{{Infobox automobile  \n|name         = Lobini H1\n|manufacturer = [[Lobini]]\n|image        = File:\u00c1guas de Lind\u00f3ia - SP Expo Carros Antigos 2011 (5909846070).jpg\n|caption      = Lobini H1\n|production   = 2005-2013\n|class        = [[Sports car]]\n|layout       = [[MR layout]]\n|related      = [[Volkswagen Golf]]<br>[[Audi A3]]<br>[[Volkswagen Fox]]<br>[[SEAT Leon]]<br>[[\u0160koda Octavia]]\n|body_style   = 2-door [[Targa top|targa]]<br>2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n|engine       = 1.8 L {{convert|178|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} [[turbocharger|turbo]] [[Straight-4|I4]] 20V\n|transmission = 5-speed manual\n}}\nThe '''Lobini H1''' is a [[sports car]] produced by the Brazilian automaker [[Lobini]]. It first appeared in 2005 and went through a minor redesign in 2007. It has a [[carbon steel]] [[tubular chassis]] and a [[fiberglass]] body shell. It makes use of a Volkswagen 1.8L [[turbocharged]] 20V engine, the same used in some versions of both [[Volkswagen Golf]] and [[Audi A3]].\n\n==Background==\nThe Lobini H1 was idealized by [[Jos\u00e9 Orlando Lobo]] and [[F\u00e1bio Birolini]], and is the first car to be produced by [[Lobini]]. It was designed by [[Graham Holmes]], former [[Lotus Cars|Lotus]] designer, and was clearly inspired by the [[Lotus Elise]]. The car's prototype was first presented to the public at the 22nd S\u00e3o Paulo Motor Show, in 2002, and the first finished unit was sold in 2005. At that time, it was only available in the [[targa top]] configuration. In 2006, minor redesigns were announced for the 2007 model. Also, at the 26th S\u00e3o Paulo Motor Show a new [[coup\u00e9]] model was introduced and a [[racing car|racing]] model was shown.\n\nThough it was well received by Brazilian enthusiasts, it is considered too expensive by most in that specific market. In fact, most of its production is directed towards the American and British markets.\n\n==Engine==\nThe H1 has an [[straight-4|I4]], 20V [[turbocharger|turbocharged]] 1.8L engine, the same as used in the Brazilian [[Volkswagen Golf GTI]], transversally mounted in front of the rear axle. It attains {{convert|178|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 5700 rpm, and makes the H1 go from 0 to {{convert|100|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} in 6.5 seconds. With this engine, the car has a maximum speed of {{convert|225|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}.\n\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Cars of Brazil]]\n\n\n{{modern-auto-stub}}\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2005]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=November 2011}}\n{{Infobox automobile  \n|name         = Lobini H1\n|manufacturer = [[Lobini]]\n|image        = File:\u00c1guas de Lind\u00f3ia - SP Expo Carros Antigos 2011 (5909846070).jpg\n|caption      = Lobini H1\n|production   = 2005-2013\n|class        = [[Sports car]]\n|layout       = [[MR layout]]\n|related      = [[Volkswagen Golf]]<br>[[Audi A3]]<br>[[Volkswagen Fox]]<br>[[SEAT Leon]]<br>[[\u0160koda Octavia]]\n|body_style   = 2-door [[Targa top|targa]]<br>2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n|engine       = 1.8 L {{convert|178|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} [[turbocharger|turbo]] [[Straight-4|I4]] 20V\n|transmission = 5-speed manual\n}}\nThe '''Lobini H1''' is a [[sports car]] produced by the Brazilian automaker [[Lobini]]. It first appeared in 2005 and went through a minor redesign in 2007. It has a [[carbon steel]] [[tubular chassis]] and a [[fiberglass]] body shell. It makes use of a Volkswagen 1.8L [[turbocharged]] 20V engine, the same used in some versions of both [[Volkswagen Golf]] and [[Audi A3]].\n\n==Background==\nThe Lobini H1 was idealized by [[Jos\u00e9 Orlando Lobo]] and [[F\u00e1bio Birolini]], and is the first car to be produced by [[Lobini]]. It was designed by [[Graham Holmes]], former [[Lotus Cars|Lotus]] designer, and was clearly inspired by the [[Lotus Elise]]. The car's prototype was first presented to the public at the 22nd S\u00e3o Paulo Motor Show, in 2002, and the first finished unit was sold in 2005. At that time, it was only available in the [[targa top]] configuration. In 2006, minor redesigns were announced for the 2007 model. Also, at the 26th S\u00e3o Paulo Motor Show a new [[coup\u00e9]] model was introduced and a [[racing car|racing]] model was shown.\n\nThough it was well received by Brazilian enthusiasts, it is considered too expensive by most in that specific market. In fact, most of its production is directed towards the American and British markets.\n\n==Engine==\nThe H1 has an [[straight-4|I4]], 20V [[turbocharger|turbocharged]] 1.8L engine, the same as used in the Brazilian [[Volkswagen Golf GTI]], transversally mounted in front of the rear axle. It attains {{convert|178|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 5700 rpm, and makes the H1 go from 0 to {{convert|100|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} in 6.5 seconds. With this engine, the car has a maximum speed of {{convert|225|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}.\n\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Cars of Brazil]]\n\n\n{{modern-auto-stub}}\n", "name_user": "TKOIII", "label": "safe", "comment": "cat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lobini_H1"}
{"title_page": "Cristiana Oprea", "text_new": "{{short description|Romanian rally driver|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n|image          = Cristiana Oprea rally driver.jpg\n|caption        = Cristiana Oprea, Romanian rally driver\n|image_size     = \n|name           = Cristiana Oprea\n|nationality    = {{flagicon|ROU}}Romanian\n|birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1992|03|11|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Bucure\u0219ti]], Romania\n|current series = [[European Rally Championship]]\n|first year     = 2019 - Rally di Roma Capitale\n|last series    = Romanian National Rally Championship, Dacia Cup\n|years active   = 2015-present\n|codriver       = Diana Ha\u021began\n|starts         = 23\n|wins           = Maximum points in ERC Ladies Trophy at Rally di Roma Capitale 2019\n|best finish    = P5 overall in Dacia Cup\n|podiums        = 2\n|year           = 2018}}\n\n'''Cristiana Oprea''' (born 11 March 1992) is a Romanian [[Rallying|rally]] driver. She is part of the very few ladies rally crews in Romania and the first Romanian woman driver to ever compete in the [[European Rally Championship]]. Her career in rallying started in 2015, first as a codriver next to George Grigorescu, then as a driver in DACIA Cup, driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe.\n\nShe competes in the Romanian National Rally Championship and in the [[European Rally Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiaerc.com/oprea-all-set-for-dream-step-up-to-erc-in-rome/|title=OPREA ALL SET FOR DREAM STEP UP TO ERC IN ROME|last=FIA ERC|website=www.fiaerc.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref> In July 2018 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first Romanian female rally crew in the last 50 years to compete in a foreign rally<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.agerpres.ro/sport/2018/07/17/auto-primul-echipaj-feminin-romanesc-din-ultimii-50-de-ani-la-un-raliu-in-afara-tarii--146346|title=Auto: Primul echipaj feminin rom\u00e2nesc din ultimii 50 de ani, la un raliu \u00een afara \u0163\u0103rii|last=AGERPRES|website=www.agerpres.ro|language=ro|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> (Rally Sliven, Bulgaria, a FIA [[European Rally Trophy]] event).\n\nIn July 2019 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first ladies crew to ever represent Romania in the FIA ERC European Rally Championship, at Rally di Roma Capitale, where they gained maximum points in the ERC Ladies Trophy standings driving a Peugeot 208 R2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiaerc.com/my-erc-debut-by-cristiana-oprea/|title=MY ERC DEBUT. BY CRISTIANA OPREA|last=FIA ERC|website=www.fiaerc.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Studies, career and motorsport debut ===\nOprea is a double graduate of the \"Ion Mincu\" University of Architecture and Urbanism in Bucharest. She studied Urban Planning (2010-2014) and Architecture (2011-2017), but she never worked in the field, wanting to follow her passion for cars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.femeia.ro/bani-cariera/cristiana-oprea-imi-doresc-sa-reprezint-romania-la-campionatul-european-de-raliuri|title=Cristiana Oprea: \u00cemi doresc s\u0103 reprezint Rom\u00e2nia la Campionatul European de Raliuri|last=-|date=2018-12-13|website=Femeia.ro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> In 2015 she was for a short while the PR of the Romanian Motorsport Federation, when she first took contact with the motorsport world. Her career in rallying started in 2015, first as a codriver next to George Grigorescu, Master of Sport and founder of the DACIA Cup series, then as a driver in DACIA Cup, driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe.\n\n==== Motorsport Excellence Centre Bucharest ====\nIn 2017, Oprea created the concept for a Motorsport Excellence Centre in Bucharest as an architecture graduation project.\n\n=== Racing career ===\nCristiana Oprea competed 2 full seasons, 2017 and 2018, in DACIA Cup,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cupadacia.ro/|title=Cupa DACIA|website=Cupa Dacia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> part of the Romanian National Rally Championship. Her rookie season was 2017, when she completed 7 events driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe with Ioana Stan as a codriver. They finished on 6th place out of 9 rookie crew and on 12th place out of 18 crews enlisted overall in DACIA Cup. In 2018 she finished on the 5th place overall in DACIA Cup, marking the best result of a woman driver since 2007, when Alina Bunica competed.\n\nOprea first stepped on a podium at the beginning of 2019 season at Arge\u0219 Rally, when together with codriver Diana Ha\u021began took second place overall<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cupadacia.ro/2019/05/07/cristi-sugar-vlad-colceriu-castiga-prima-etapa-cristiana-oprea-diana-hategan-scriu-istorie-in-cupa-dacia-la-raliul-argesului/|title=Cristi Sugar/Vlad Colceriu c\u00e2\u0219tig\u0103 prima etap\u0103, Cristiana Oprea/Diana Ha\u021began scriu istorie \u00een Cupa DACIA la Raliul Arge\u0219ului|date=2019-05-07|website=Cupa Dacia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> in DACIA Cup.\n\nIn July 2019 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first ladies crew to ever represent Romania in the FIA ERC European Rally Championship, at Rally di Roma Capitale, where they finished P8 in the highly competitive ERC3 class and gained maximum points in the ERC Ladies Trophy standings.\n\n=== Romanian Women in Motorsport platform ===\nOprea is the founder and administrator of \"Femei \u00een Motorsport\", a platform dedicated to promoting all women involved in Romanian motorsport, following the Women in Motorsport concept as defined by FIA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://autostiri.ro/femei-motorsport-o-pagina-dedicata-promovarii-femeilor-implicate-automobilismul-si-motociclismul-din-romania/|title=Femei in motorsport, o pagina dedicata promov\u0103rii femeilor implicate \u00een automobilismul \u0219i motociclismul din Rom\u00e2nia|last=Strauti|first=Dan|date=2019-03-01|website=Autostiri.ro|language=ro-RO|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n==Notes==\n* [https://emoticar.ro/en/home/ Official website]\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Romanian rally drivers]]\n[[Category:Female rally drivers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Romanian rally driver|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n|image=[[File:Cristiana Oprea rally driver.jpg|thumb|Cristiana Oprea, Romanian rally driver]]\n|image_size =\n|name=Cristiana Oprea\n|nationality={{flagicon|ROU}}Romanian\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1992|03|11|df=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Bucure\u0219ti]], Romania\n|current series=[[European Rally Championship]]\n| first year        =2019 - Rally di Roma Capitale\n|last series=Romanian National Rally Championship, Dacia Cup\n|years active=2015-present\n|codriver=Diana Ha\u021began\n|starts=23\n| wins              = Maximum points in ERC Ladies Trophy at Rally di Roma Capitale 2019\n| best finish       = P5 overall in Dacia Cup\n| podiums           =2\n|year=2018}}\n\n'''Cristiana Oprea''' (born 11 March 1992) is a Romanian [[Rallying|rally]] driver. She is part of the very few ladies rally crews in Romania and the first Romanian woman driver to ever compete in the [[European Rally Championship]]. Her career in rallying started in 2015, first as a codriver next to George Grigorescu, then as a driver in DACIA Cup, driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe.\n\nShe competes in the Romanian National Rally Championship and in the [[European Rally Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiaerc.com/oprea-all-set-for-dream-step-up-to-erc-in-rome/|title=OPREA ALL SET FOR DREAM STEP UP TO ERC IN ROME|last=FIA ERC|website=www.fiaerc.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref> In July 2018 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first Romanian female rally crew in the last 50 years to compete in a foreign rally<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.agerpres.ro/sport/2018/07/17/auto-primul-echipaj-feminin-romanesc-din-ultimii-50-de-ani-la-un-raliu-in-afara-tarii--146346|title=Auto: Primul echipaj feminin rom\u00e2nesc din ultimii 50 de ani, la un raliu \u00een afara \u0163\u0103rii|last=AGERPRES|website=www.agerpres.ro|language=ro|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> (Rally Sliven, Bulgaria, a FIA [[European Rally Trophy]] event).\n\nIn July 2019 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first ladies crew to ever represent Romania in the FIA ERC European Rally Championship, at Rally di Roma Capitale, where they gained maximum points in the ERC Ladies Trophy standings driving a Peugeot 208 R2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiaerc.com/my-erc-debut-by-cristiana-oprea/|title=MY ERC DEBUT. BY CRISTIANA OPREA|last=FIA ERC|website=www.fiaerc.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Studies, career and motorsport debut ===\nOprea is a double graduate of the \"Ion Mincu\" University of Architecture and Urbanism in Bucharest. She studied Urban Planning (2010-2014) and Architecture (2011-2017), but she never worked in the field, wanting to follow her passion for cars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.femeia.ro/bani-cariera/cristiana-oprea-imi-doresc-sa-reprezint-romania-la-campionatul-european-de-raliuri|title=Cristiana Oprea: \u00cemi doresc s\u0103 reprezint Rom\u00e2nia la Campionatul European de Raliuri|last=-|date=2018-12-13|website=Femeia.ro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> In 2015 she was for a short while the PR of the Romanian Motorsport Federation, when she first took contact with the motorsport world. Her career in rallying started in 2015, first as a codriver next to George Grigorescu, Master of Sport and founder of the DACIA Cup series, then as a driver in DACIA Cup, driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe.\n\n==== Motorsport Excellence Centre Bucharest ====\nIn 2017, Oprea created the concept for a Motorsport Excellence Centre in Bucharest as an architecture graduation project.\n\n=== Racing career ===\nCristiana Oprea competed 2 full seasons, 2017 and 2018, in DACIA Cup,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cupadacia.ro/|title=Cupa DACIA|website=Cupa Dacia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> part of the Romanian National Rally Championship. Her rookie season was 2017, when she completed 7 events driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe with Ioana Stan as a codriver. They finished on 6th place out of 9 rookie crew and on 12th place out of 18 crews enlisted overall in DACIA Cup. In 2018 she finished on the 5th place overall in DACIA Cup, marking the best result of a woman driver since 2007, when Alina Bunica competed.\n\nOprea first stepped on a podium at the beginning of 2019 season at Arge\u0219 Rally, when together with codriver Diana Ha\u021began took second place overall<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cupadacia.ro/2019/05/07/cristi-sugar-vlad-colceriu-castiga-prima-etapa-cristiana-oprea-diana-hategan-scriu-istorie-in-cupa-dacia-la-raliul-argesului/|title=Cristi Sugar/Vlad Colceriu c\u00e2\u0219tig\u0103 prima etap\u0103, Cristiana Oprea/Diana Ha\u021began scriu istorie \u00een Cupa DACIA la Raliul Arge\u0219ului|date=2019-05-07|website=Cupa Dacia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> in DACIA Cup.\n\nIn July 2019 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first ladies crew to ever represent Romania in the FIA ERC European Rally Championship, at Rally di Roma Capitale, where they finished P8 in the highly competitive ERC3 class and gained maximum points in the ERC Ladies Trophy standings.\n\n=== Romanian Women in Motorsport platform ===\nOprea is the founder and administrator of \"Femei \u00een Motorsport\", a platform dedicated to promoting all women involved in Romanian motorsport, following the Women in Motorsport concept as defined by FIA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://autostiri.ro/femei-motorsport-o-pagina-dedicata-promovarii-femeilor-implicate-automobilismul-si-motociclismul-din-romania/|title=Femei in motorsport, o pagina dedicata promov\u0103rii femeilor implicate \u00een automobilismul \u0219i motociclismul din Rom\u00e2nia|last=Strauti|first=Dan|date=2019-03-01|website=Autostiri.ro|language=ro-RO|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n==Notes==\n* [https://emoticar.ro/en/home/ Official website]\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Romanian rally drivers]]\n[[Category:Female rally drivers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cristiana_Oprea"}
{"title_page": "Lechia-Polonia Gda\u0144sk", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Lechia-Polonia Gda\u0144sk\n| image =\n| fullname = Lechia-Polonia Gda\u0144sk Sportowa Sp\u00f3\u0142ka Akcyjna\n| founded = 1998\n| dissolved = 2002\n| ground = [[MOSiR Stadium (Gda\u0144sk)|MOSiR Stadium]]\n| capacity = 12,244\n| manager = [[Witold Kulik]] & [[Stanis\u0142aw Stachura]] (1998\u201399)<br>[[Jerzy Jastrz\u0119bowski]] (1999\u20132000)<br>[[Wies\u0142aw Wika]] (2000)<br>[[Romuald Szukie\u0142owicz]] (2000)<br>[[Stanis\u0142aw Stachura]] (2000\u201302)\n| pattern_la1=FFFFFF|pattern_b1=_lechiapolonia200102h|pattern_ra1=FFFFFF\n|  leftarm1=|body1=|rightarm1=|pattern_sh1=_olimpialechia199596h|socks1=07763a| pattern_name1 = 2001\u20132002 Home\n|  pattern_la2=_lechiapolonia200102a|pattern_b2=_lechiapolonia200102a|pattern_ra2=_lechiapolonia200102a\n|  leftarm2=|body2=|rightarm2=|shorts2=07763a|socks2=FFFFFF|pattern_name2 = 2001\u20132002 Away\n}}\n'''Lechia-Polonia Gda\u0144sk''' is a now defunct team which played in the Polish second division from 1998\u20132001. The team was created by a merger of [[Lechia Gda\u0144sk]] and [[Polonia Gda\u0144sk]].\n\n== History ==\n\n===Pre-merger===\n\n====Polonia Gda\u0144sk==== \n{{main|Polonia Gda\u0144sk}}\n\nPolonia Gda\u0144sk were founded in 1945 as NS Nit Gda\u0144sk. After years of playing football in the lower divisions, and further name changes (Stal Gda\u0144sk and RKS Stoczniowiec Gda\u0144sk <ref name=\"poloniagdansk1\">{{cite web|url=http://poloniagdansk.pl/?page_id=2578|title=Historia -|website=poloniagdansk.pl}}</ref>). The team finally found stability and were called [[Polonia Gda\u0144sk]].<ref name=\"poloniagdansk1\"/>\n\nThe team finally achieved promotion to the second division in 1973 after winning their division, and finishing as runners up the previous season. The 1970s saw the team's high point in their history. The team enjoyed 9 seasons in the second division before being relegated in 1982. The team's greatest achievement so far came in the 1976/77 season when the team finished 3rd, just missing out on promotion to the top division.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hppn.pl/liga/sezon-po-sezonie/35,sezon-1976-77/100,II-liga-grupa-polnocna/tabela|title=Sezon 1976/77 - II liga (gr. p\u00f3\u0142nocna)  - tabela rozgrywek - Historia Polskiej Pi\u0142ki No\u017cnej - HPPN.PL|website=www.hppn.pl}}</ref> From 1982-1998 Polonia experienced another 3 seasons in the second tier, each time only lasting in the division for one season. The team won the third tier 3 times during this period, as well as finishing runners up a further 5 times.\n\n====Lechia Gda\u0144sk====\n{{main|Lechia Gda\u0144sk}}\n\n[[Lechia Gda\u0144sk]] were also founded in 1945.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/teams/lechia-gdansk/21/|title=Lechia Gda\u0144sk - Historical results|website=worldfootball.net}}</ref> Lechia's greatest success in the top flight came during the 1950s, when the club finished 3rd during the 1956 season. After spending the 1960s and 70s in the lower divisions, Lechia won the [[Polish Cup]] and the [[Polish SuperCup]] in 1983. After a spell back in the top flight, Lechia soon found themselves playing in the lower divisions once more. During the 1995 season, Lechia had previously been part of another merger, this time with [[Olimpia Pozna\u0144]] to create [[Olimpia-Lechia Gda\u0144sk]]. The merger lasted only one season before both teams split. It was only two seasons after their first merger that Lechia were to be involved in another, this time with Polonia.\n\n=== Lechia-Polonia Gda\u0144sk ===\n\nThe first season for Lechia-Polonia was moderately successful. The previous season Polonia finished in 5th place, for the 1998\u201399 season Lechia-Polonia managed to achieve 7th in the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mogiel.net/POL/history/2w99.php |title=Stats |website=www.mogiel.net |format=PHP}}</ref> The following season was more unsuccessful, finishing the season in 14th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mogiel.net/POL/2-00.php |title=Stats |website=www.mogiel.net |format=PHP}}</ref> Robert Kubiel finished as the team's highest goalscorer with 10 goals to his name.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lechia.net/klub/historia/mecze-lg-1945/roster/23-19992000-ii-liga/1-lechia-gdask/0# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-11-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112021551/https://lechia.net/klub/historia/mecze-lg-1945/roster/23-19992000-ii-liga/1-lechia-gdask/0# |archive-date=2018-11-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The following season got worse for Lechia-Polonia, with the team finishing 19th out of 20 teams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mogiel.net/POL/2-01.php |title=Stats |website=www.mogiel.net |format=PHP}}</ref> Despite being in a lower division the team proved to be less than competitive, and the team once again faced relegation, this time finishing in 15th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.90minut.pl/liga/0/liga82.html|title=III liga 2001/2002, grupa: 2 (Pomorze Zachodnie, Pomorze, Wielkopolska, Kujawy i Pomorze)|first=Maciej|last=Kusina|website=www.90minut.pl}}</ref> After the 2001\u201302 season, the Lechia-Polonia dissolved.\n\n=== After the merger ===\n\n[[Polonia Gda\u0144sk]] created a separate team in 1999, one year after the merger. Despite the team still being involved in the merger by name, most saw this as the teams continuation of the original team, and not the Lechia-Polonia team. The reforming meant that Polonia had to restart from Poland's lowest divisions. The highest the team has achieved since the turn of the century was 2 seasons in the third division, finishing 14th and 16th from 2012\u201314. Back to back relegation's meant the team were playing in the firth tier once again, and currently find themselves playing in the District Division - Gda\u0144sk Group I.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://poloniagdansk.pl/?page_id=22|title=Pierwsza dru\u017cyna -|website=poloniagdansk.pl}}</ref>\n\n[[Lechia Gda\u0144sk]] also created a separate team from the Lechia-Polonia team in 2001, and was also seen as the continuation of the team before the merger. In 2001 there was therefor 3 teams playing football as a result of the merger; Lechia-Polonia Gda\u0144sk, Lechia Gda\u0144sk, and Polonia Gda\u0144sk. While the dissolved Lechia-Polonia team left both Lechia and Polonia in much worse positions than before the merger, Lechia took full advantage of the situation they found themselves in. After having to start from the bottom, Lechia's fortunes changed and they found themselves playing in the Ekstraklasa once again for the 2008/09 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.90minut.pl/news.php?id=725500|title=Lechia Gda\u0144sk awansowa\u0142a do ekstraklasy|website=www.90minut.pl}}</ref> After 11 seasons of continuous top flight football Lechia won both the [[Polish Cup]] and the [[Polish SuperCup]] in 2019, leading to the team playing European football for only the second time in their history.\n\n==Seasons==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n! Season\n! Tier\n! Division\n! Position\n! Polish Cup\n!colspan=2|Comments\n|-\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#d0e7ff\"|1998/99||bgcolor=\"#d0e7ff\" rowspan=3|II||bgcolor=\"#d0e7ff\"|II League (west)||7 of 14||Round of 16||style=\"font-size:85%\" colspan=2|Team created by a merger between [[Lechia Gda\u0144sk]] and [[Polonia Gda\u0144sk]].\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#d0e7ff\"|1999/00||bgcolor=\"#d0e7ff\"|II League||14 of 24||Round of 16||style=\"font-size:85%\" colspan=2|[[Polonia Gda\u0144sk]] left the merger, restarting in the IV liga (sixth tier).\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#d0e7ff\"|2000/01||bgcolor=\"#d0e7ff\"|II League||bgcolor=\"#FFCCCC\"|19 of 20||Round 2||style=\"font-size:85%\" colspan=2|Lechia-Polonia Gda\u0144sk are relegated.\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#fff3c0\"|2001/02||bgcolor=\"#fff3c0\"|III||bgcolor=\"#fff3c0\"|III League (g. 2)||bgcolor=\"#FFCCCC\"|15 of 19||-||style=\"font-size:85%\"|[[Lechia Gda\u0144sk]] create an independent club at the start of the season, restarting in the IV liga (sixth tier).||style=\"font-size:85%\"|Lechia-Polonia Gda\u0144sk suffer financial difficulties and fold at the end of the season.\n|}\n\n==Kits==\n\nThe kits worn by Lechia-Polonia during their four seasons of existence.\n{|\n|{{Football kit box|pattern_la=_lechiapolonia19982000h|pattern_b=_lechiapolonia19982000h|pattern_ra=_lechiapolonia19982000h|leftarm=|body=|rightarm=|shorts=07763a|socks=07763a|title=1998\u20132000 home kit}}\n|{{Football kit box|pattern_la=_lechiapolonia19982000a|pattern_b=_lechiapolonia19982000a|pattern_ra=_lechiapolonia19982000a|leftarm=|body=|rightarm=|shorts=FFFFFF|socks=FFFFFF|title=1998\u20132000 away kit}}\n|{{Football kit box|pattern_la=_lechiapolonia200001h3|pattern_b=_lechiapolonia200001h|pattern_ra=_lechiapolonia200001h3|leftarm=|body=|rightarm=|pattern_sh=FFFFFF|socks=07763a|title=2000-01 home kit}}\n|{{Football kit box|pattern_la=_lechiapolonia200001a|pattern_b=_lechiapolonia200001a|pattern_ra=_lechiapolonia200001a|leftarm=|body=|rightarm=|pattern_sh=FFFFFF|socks=FFFFFF|title=2000-01 away kit}}\n|{{Football kit box|pattern_la=FFFFFF|pattern_b=_lechiapolonia200102h|pattern_ra=FFFFFF|leftarm=|body=|rightarm=|pattern_sh=_olimpialechia199596h|socks=07763a|title=2001-02 home kit}}\n|{{Football kit box|pattern_la=_lechiapolonia200102a|pattern_b=_lechiapolonia200102a|pattern_ra=_lechiapolonia200102a|leftarm=|body=|rightarm=|shorts=07763a|socks=FFFFFF|title=2001-02 away kit}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct football clubs in Poland]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1998]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Poland]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs disestablished in 2002]]\n[[Category:2002 disestablishments in Poland]]\n[[Category:Sport in Gda\u0144sk]]\n[[Category:Lechia Gda\u0144sk]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Lechia-Polonia Gda\u0144sk\n| image =\n| fullname = Lechia-Polonia Gda\u0144sk Sportowa Sp\u00f3\u0142ka Akcyjna\n| founded = 1998\n| dissolved = 2002\n| ground = [[MOSiR Stadium (Gda\u0144sk)|MOSiR Stadium]]\n| capacity = 12,244\n| manager = [[Witold Kulik]] & [[Stanis\u0142aw Stachura]] (1998\u201399)<br>[[Jerzy Jastrz\u0119bowski]] (1999\u20132000)<br>[[Wies\u0142aw Wika]] (2000)<br>[[Romuald Szukie\u0142owicz]] (2000)<br>[[Stanis\u0142aw Stachura]] (2000\u201302)\n| pattern_la1=FFFFFF|pattern_b1=_lechiapolonia200102h|pattern_ra1=FFFFFF\n|  leftarm1=|body1=|rightarm1=|pattern_sh1=_olimpialechia199596h|socks1=07763a| pattern_name1 = 2001\u20132002 Home\n|  pattern_la2=_lechiapolonia200102a|pattern_b2=_lechiapolonia200102a|pattern_ra2=_lechiapolonia200102a\n|  leftarm2=|body2=|rightarm2=|shorts2=07763a|socks2=FFFFFF|pattern_name2 = 2001\u20132002 Away\n}}\n'''Lechia-Polonia Gda\u0144sk''' is a now defunct team which played in the Polish second division from 1998\u20132001. The team was created by a merger of [[Lechia Gda\u0144sk]] and [[Polonia Gda\u0144sk]].\n\n== History ==\n\n===Pre-merger===\n\n====Polonia Gda\u0144sk==== \n{{main|Polonia Gda\u0144sk}}\n\nPolonia Gda\u0144sk were founded in 1945 as NS Nit Gda\u0144sk. After years of playing football in the lower divisions, and further name changes (Stal Gda\u0144sk and RKS Stoczniowiec Gda\u0144sk <ref name=\"poloniagdansk1\">{{cite web|url=http://poloniagdansk.pl/?page_id=2578|title=Historia -|website=poloniagdansk.pl}}</ref>). The team finally found stability and were called [[Polonia Gda\u0144sk]].<ref name=\"poloniagdansk1\"/>\n\nThe team finally achieved promotion to the second division in 1973 after winning their division, and finishing as runners up the previous season. The 1970s saw the teams high point in their history. The team enjoyed 9 seasons in the second division before being relegated in 1982. The teams greatest achievement so far came in the 1976/77 season when the team finished 3rd, just missing out on promotion to the top division.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hppn.pl/liga/sezon-po-sezonie/35,sezon-1976-77/100,II-liga-grupa-polnocna/tabela|title=Sezon 1976/77 - II liga (gr. p\u00f3\u0142nocna)  - tabela rozgrywek - Historia Polskiej Pi\u0142ki No\u017cnej - HPPN.PL|website=www.hppn.pl}}</ref> From 1982-1998 Polonia experienced another 3 seasons in the second tier, each time only lasting in the division for one season. The team won the third tier 3 times during this period, as well as finishing runners up a further 5 times.\n\n====Lechia Gda\u0144sk====\n{{main|Lechia Gda\u0144sk}}\n\n[[Lechia Gda\u0144sk]] were also founded in 1945.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/teams/lechia-gdansk/21/|title=Lechia Gda\u0144sk - Historical results|website=worldfootball.net}}</ref> Lechia's greatest success in the top flight came during the 1950s, when the club finished 3rd during the 1956 season. After spending the 1960s and 70s in the lower divisions, Lechia won the [[Polish Cup]] and the [[Polish SuperCup]] in 1983. After a spell back in the top flight, Lechia soon found themselves playing in the lower divisions once more. During the 1995 season, Lechia had previously been part of another merger, this time with [[Olimpia Pozna\u0144]] to create [[Olimpia-Lechia Gda\u0144sk]]. The merger lasted only one season before both teams split. It was only two seasons after their first merger that Lechia were to be involved in another, this time with Polonia.\n\n=== Lechia-Polonia Gda\u0144sk ===\n\nThe first season for Lechia-Polonia was moderately successful. The previous season Polonia finished in 5th place, for the 1998\u201399 season Lechia-Polonia managed to achieve 7th in the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mogiel.net/POL/history/2w99.php |title=Stats |website=www.mogiel.net |format=PHP}}</ref> The following season was more unsuccessful, finishing the season in 14th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mogiel.net/POL/2-00.php |title=Stats |website=www.mogiel.net |format=PHP}}</ref> Robert Kubiel finished as the teams highest goalscorer with 10 goals to his name.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lechia.net/klub/historia/mecze-lg-1945/roster/23-19992000-ii-liga/1-lechia-gdask/0# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-11-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112021551/https://lechia.net/klub/historia/mecze-lg-1945/roster/23-19992000-ii-liga/1-lechia-gdask/0# |archive-date=2018-11-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The following season got worse for Lechia-Polonia, with the team finishing 19th out of 20 teams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mogiel.net/POL/2-01.php |title=Stats |website=www.mogiel.net |format=PHP}}</ref> Despite being in a lower division the team proved to be less than competitive, and the team once again faced relegation, this time finishing in 15th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.90minut.pl/liga/0/liga82.html|title=III liga 2001/2002, grupa: 2 (Pomorze Zachodnie, Pomorze, Wielkopolska, Kujawy i Pomorze)|first=Maciej|last=Kusina|website=www.90minut.pl}}</ref> After the 2001\u201302 season, the Lechia-Polonia dissolved.\n\n=== After the merger ===\n\n[[Polonia Gda\u0144sk]] created a separate team in 1999, one year after the merger. Despite the team still being involved in the merger by name, most saw this as the teams continuation of the original team, and not the Lechia-Polonia team. The reforming meant that Polonia had to restart from Poland's lowest divisions. The highest the team has achieved since the turn of the century was 2 seasons in the third division, finishing 14th and 16th from 2012\u201314. Back to back relegation's meant the team were playing in the firth tier once again, and currently find themselves playing in the District Division - Gda\u0144sk Group I.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://poloniagdansk.pl/?page_id=22|title=Pierwsza dru\u017cyna -|website=poloniagdansk.pl}}</ref>\n\n[[Lechia Gda\u0144sk]] also created a separate team from the Lechia-Polonia team in 2001, and was also seen as the continuation of the team before the merger. In 2001 there was therefor 3 teams playing football as a result of the merger; Lechia-Polonia Gda\u0144sk, Lechia Gda\u0144sk, and Polonia Gda\u0144sk. While the dissolved Lechia-Polonia team left both Lechia and Polonia in much worse positions than before the merger, Lechia took full advantage of the situation they found themselves in. After having to start from the bottom, Lechia's fortunes changed and they found themselves playing in the Ekstraklasa once again for the 2008/09 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.90minut.pl/news.php?id=725500|title=Lechia Gda\u0144sk awansowa\u0142a do ekstraklasy|website=www.90minut.pl}}</ref> After 11 seasons of continuous top flight football Lechia won both the [[Polish Cup]] and the [[Polish SuperCup]] in 2019, leading to the team playing European football for only the second time in their history.\n\n==Seasons==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n! Season\n! Tier\n! Division\n! Position\n! Polish Cup\n!colspan=2|Comments\n|-\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#d0e7ff\"|1998/99||bgcolor=\"#d0e7ff\" rowspan=3|II||bgcolor=\"#d0e7ff\"|II League (west)||7 of 14||Round of 16||style=\"font-size:85%\" colspan=2|Team created by a merger between [[Lechia Gda\u0144sk]] and [[Polonia Gda\u0144sk]].\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#d0e7ff\"|1999/00||bgcolor=\"#d0e7ff\"|II League||14 of 24||Round of 16||style=\"font-size:85%\" colspan=2|[[Polonia Gda\u0144sk]] left the merger, restarting in the IV liga (sixth tier).\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#d0e7ff\"|2000/01||bgcolor=\"#d0e7ff\"|II League||bgcolor=\"#FFCCCC\"|19 of 20||Round 2||style=\"font-size:85%\" colspan=2|Lechia-Polonia Gda\u0144sk are relegated.\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#fff3c0\"|2001/02||bgcolor=\"#fff3c0\"|III||bgcolor=\"#fff3c0\"|III League (g. 2)||bgcolor=\"#FFCCCC\"|15 of 19||-||style=\"font-size:85%\"|[[Lechia Gda\u0144sk]] create an independent club at the start of the season, restarting in the IV liga (sixth tier).||style=\"font-size:85%\"|Lechia-Polonia Gda\u0144sk suffer financial difficulties and fold at the end of the season.\n|}\n\n==Kits==\n\nThe kits worn by Lechia-Polonia during their four seasons of existence.\n{|\n|{{Football kit box|pattern_la=_lechiapolonia19982000h|pattern_b=_lechiapolonia19982000h|pattern_ra=_lechiapolonia19982000h|leftarm=|body=|rightarm=|shorts=07763a|socks=07763a|title=1998\u20132000 home kit}}\n|{{Football kit box|pattern_la=_lechiapolonia19982000a|pattern_b=_lechiapolonia19982000a|pattern_ra=_lechiapolonia19982000a|leftarm=|body=|rightarm=|shorts=FFFFFF|socks=FFFFFF|title=1998\u20132000 away kit}}\n|{{Football kit box|pattern_la=_lechiapolonia200001h3|pattern_b=_lechiapolonia200001h|pattern_ra=_lechiapolonia200001h3|leftarm=|body=|rightarm=|pattern_sh=FFFFFF|socks=07763a|title=2000-01 home kit}}\n|{{Football kit box|pattern_la=_lechiapolonia200001a|pattern_b=_lechiapolonia200001a|pattern_ra=_lechiapolonia200001a|leftarm=|body=|rightarm=|pattern_sh=FFFFFF|socks=FFFFFF|title=2000-01 away kit}}\n|{{Football kit box|pattern_la=FFFFFF|pattern_b=_lechiapolonia200102h|pattern_ra=FFFFFF|leftarm=|body=|rightarm=|pattern_sh=_olimpialechia199596h|socks=07763a|title=2001-02 home kit}}\n|{{Football kit box|pattern_la=_lechiapolonia200102a|pattern_b=_lechiapolonia200102a|pattern_ra=_lechiapolonia200102a|leftarm=|body=|rightarm=|shorts=07763a|socks=FFFFFF|title=2001-02 away kit}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct football clubs in Poland]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1998]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Poland]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs disestablished in 2002]]\n[[Category:2002 disestablishments in Poland]]\n[[Category:Sport in Gda\u0144sk]]\n[[Category:Lechia Gda\u0144sk]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing, replaced: teams high \u2192 team's high (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lechia-Polonia_Gda%C5%84sk"}
{"title_page": "Emergent virus", "text_new": "An '''emergent virus''' (or '''emerging virus''') is a [[virus]] that is either newly [[Viral evolution|appeared]], notably increasing in [[incidence (epidemiology)|incidence]]/[[geographic range limit|geographic range]] or has the potential to increase in the near future.<ref name=\"Holland\">{{cite journal |last1=Holland |first1=DJ |title=Emerging Viruses |journal=Current Opinion in Pediatrics |date=1998 |volume=10 |pages=34-40 |pmid=9529635\n|doi=10.1097/00008480-199802000-00007}}</ref> Emergent viruses are a leading cause of [[emerging infectious disease]]s and raise [[public health]] challenges globally, given their potential to cause [[disease outbreak|outbreak]]s of disease which can lead to [[epidemic]]s and [[pandemic]]s.<ref name=\"Devaux2012\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Devaux CA |title=Emerging and re-emerging viruses: A global challenge illustrated by Chikungunya virus outbreaks |journal=World J Virol |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=11\u201322 |date=2012 |pmid=24175207 |pmc=3782263 |doi=10.5501/wjv.v1.i1.11 |url=}}</ref> Recent examples include the [[SARS-related coronavirus]]es, which have caused the [[2002-2004 SARS outbreak|2002-2004 outbreak]] of [[severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] ([[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus|SARS-CoV-1]]) and the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] ([[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]).<ref name=\"Zheng2020\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Zheng J |title=SARS-CoV-2: an Emerging Coronavirus that Causes a Global Threat |journal=International Journal of Biological Sciences |volume=16 |issue=10 |pages=1678\u201385 |date=2020 |pmid=32226285 |pmc=7098030 |doi=10.7150/ijbs.45053 |url=}}</ref> Other examples include the [[human immunodeficiency virus]] which causes [[HIV/AIDS]]; the viruses responsible for [[Ebola]];<ref name=\"Holmes2016\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Holmes EC, Dudas G, Rambaut A, Andersen KG |title=The evolution of Ebola virus: Insights from the 2013-2016 epidemic |journal=Nature |volume=538 |issue=7624 |pages=193\u2013200 |date=2016 |pmid=27734858 |pmc=5580494 |doi=10.1038/nature19790 |url=}}</ref> the [[H5N1]] influenza virus responsible for [[avian flu]];<ref name=\"Wei2016\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Wei P, Cai Z, Hua J, et al. |title=Pains and Gains from China's Experiences with Emerging Epidemics: From SARS to H7N9 |journal=Biomed Res Int |volume=2016 |issue= |pages=5717108 |date=2016 |pmid=27525272 |pmc=4971293 |doi=10.1155/2016/5717108 |url=}}</ref> and [[H1N1/09]], which caused the [[2009 swine flu]] pandemic.<ref name=\"Smith2009\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Smith GJ, Vijaykrishna D, Bahl J, et al. |title=Origins and evolutionary genomics of the 2009 swine-origin H1N1 influenza A epidemic |journal=Nature |volume=459 |issue=7250 |pages=1122\u20135 |date=2009 |pmid=19516283 |doi=10.1038/nature08182 |url=}}</ref> An earlier emergent [[Viral strain|strain]] of [[H1N1]] caused the 1918 [[Spanish flu]] pandemic.<ref name=\"Taubenberger2006\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Taubenberger JK, Morens DM |title=1918 Influenza: the mother of all pandemics |journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=15\u201322 |date=2006 |pmid=16494711 |pmc=3291398 |doi=10.3201/eid1201.050979}}</ref> The most frequent cause of viral emergence in humans is [[zoonosis]], which involves a [[Cross-species transmission|cross-species jump]] of a [[viral disease]] into humans from other animals. As zoonotic viruses exist in [[Natural reservoir|animal reservoir]]s, they are much more difficult to [[eradication of infectious diseases|eradicate]] and can therefore establish persistent infections in human populations.<ref name=\"Eidson\">{{cite web |last1=Eidson |first1=M |title=Zoonotic disease |url=https://www.britannica.com/science/zoonotic-disease |publisher=Britannica |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nEmergent viruses should not be confused with '''re-emerging viruses''' and '''newly-detected viruses'''. A re-emerging virus is generally considered to be a previously appeared virus that is experiencing a resurgence<ref name=\"Holland\"/><ref name=\"Porta2008\">{{cite book |editor=Miquel Porta |title=A Dictionary of Epidemiology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3Dr8dyuzvTkC |year=2008 |publisher=Oxford University Press, USA |isbn=978-0-19-971815-3 |page=78}}</ref> - for example, [[measles]] is re-emerging as a serious public health threat, with outbreaks occurring in even highly developed countries.<ref name=\"Poland\">{{cite journal |last1=Poland |first1=GA |last2=Jacobson |first2=RM |title=The Re-Emergence of Measles in Developed Countries: Time to Develop the Next-Generation Measles Vaccines? |journal=Vaccine |date=2012 |volume=30(2) |page=103-4 |doi=10.1016/j.vaccine.2011.11.085 |pmid=22196079}}</ref> A newly-detected virus is a previously unrecognized virus that had been circulating in the species as [[endemic (epidemiology)|endemic]] or epidemic infections.<ref name=\"Woolhouse2\">{{cite journal |last1=Woolhouse |first1=M |last2=Scott |first2=F |last3=Hudson |first3=Z |last4=Howey |first4=R |last5=Chase-Topping |first5=M |title=Human viruses: discovery and emergence |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society London B Biological Science |date=2012 |volume=367(1604) |doi=10.1098/rstb.2011.0354 |pmid=22966141}}</ref> Newly-detected viruses may have escaped [[Virus classification|classification]] because they left no distinctive [[Disease surveillance|clues]], and/or could not be isolated or propagated in [[Viral culture|cell culture]].<ref name=\"Leland\">{{cite journal |last1=Leland |first1=DS |last2=Ginocchio |first2=CC |title=Role of Cell Culture for Virus Detection in the Age of Technology |journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews |date=2007 |volume=20(1) |doi=10.1128/CMR.00002-06 |pmid=17223623}}</ref> Examples include [[rhinovirus|human rhinovirus]] (a leading cause of common colds which was first identified in 1956),<ref name=Kennedy2012>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kennedy JL, Turner RB, Braciale T, Heymann PW, Borish L |title=Pathogenesis of rhinovirus infection |journal=Current Opinion in Virology |volume=2 |issue=3 |pages=287\u201393 |date=2012 |pmid=22542099 |pmc=3378761 |doi=10.1016/j.coviro.2012.03.008}}</ref> [[hepatitis C]] (eventually identified in 1989),<ref name=Houghton>{{cite journal |vauthors=Houghton M | authorlink=Michael Houghton (virologist) |title=The long and winding road leading to the identification of the hepatitis C virus |journal=Journal of Hepatology |volume=51 |issue=5 |pages=939\u201348 |date=2009 |pmid=19781804 |doi=10.1016/j.jhep.2009.08.004 |url=http://www.journal-of-hepatology.eu/article/S0168-8278%2809%2900535-2/fulltext}}</ref>  and [[human metapneumovirus]] (first described in 2001, but thought to have been circulating since the 19th century).<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=de Graaf M, Osterhaus AD, Fouchier RA, Holmes EC |title=Evolutionary dynamics of human and avian metapneumoviruses |journal=The Journal of General Virology |volume=89  |issue=12 |pages=2933\u20132942 |date=2008 |pmid=19008378 |doi=10.1099/vir.0.2008/006957-0 |url=}}</ref> As the detection of such viruses is technology driven, the number reported is likely to expand.\n\n==Zoonosis==\n{{See also|Zoonosis}}\nGiven the rarity of spontaneous development of new virus species, the most frequent cause of emergent viruses in humans is [[zoonosis]]. This phenomenon is estimated to account for 73% of all [[Emerging infectious disease|emerging or re-emerging pathogens]], with viruses playing a disproportionately large role.<ref name=\"Woolhouse\"/> [[RNA virus]]es are particularly frequent, accounting for 37% of emerging and re-emerging pathogens.<ref name=\"Woolhouse\">{{cite journal |last1=Woolhouse |first1=ME | authorlink=Mark Woolhouse | last2=Gowtage-Sequeria |first2=S| title=Host Range and Emerging and Reemerging Pathogens |journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases |date=2005 |volume=11 |page=1842-7 |pmid=16485468 |pmc=3367654 |doi=10.3201/eid1112.050997}}</ref> A broad range of animals - including wild birds, rodents and bats - are associated with zoonotic viruses.<ref name=\"Kruse\">{{cite journal |last1=Kruse |first1=H |last2=Kirkemo|first2=A |last3=Handeland |first3=K |title=Wildlife as Source of Zoonotic Infections |journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases |date=2004 |volume=10(12) |page=2067-2072 |doi=10.3201/eid1012.040707 |pmid=15663840 |pmc=3323390}}</ref> It is not possible to predict specific zoonotic events that may be associated with a particular animal reservoir at any given time.<ref name=\"Domingo\"/>\n\n[[Spillover infection|Zoonotic spillover]] can either result in self-limited infections, in which no further human-human transmission occurs (as with the [[rabies|rabies virus]]), or in infectious cases, in which the zoonotic pathogen is able to sustain human-human transmission (as with the [[Ebola|Ebola virus]]). If the zoonotic virus is able to maintain successful human-human transmission, an [[Disease outbreak|outbreak]] may occur.<ref name=Parrish>{{cite journal | last1 = Parrish | first1 = CR | last2 = Holmes | first2 = EC | last3 = Morens | first3 = DM | display-authors = etal | title = Cross-Species Virus Transmission and the Emergence of New Epidemic Diseases | journal = Microbiology and Molecular Biology Reviews | volume = 72 | issue = 3 | pages = 457\u2013470 | date = 2008 | doi =10.1128/MMBR.00004-08 | pmid=18772285 | pmc=2546865}}</ref> Some spillover events can also result in the virus adapting exclusively for human infection (as occurred with the [[HIV|HIV virus]]), in which case humans become a new reservoir for the pathogen.\n\nA successful zoonotic 'jump' depends on human contact with an animal harbouring a virus variant that is able to infect humans. A virus originating from an animal reservoir will normally undergo [[mutation]], [[genetic recombination]] and [[reassortment]] so as to allow it to extend its [[host range|range of infectable species]] to include humans, and to sustain efficient human-human transmission.<ref name=\"Domingo\">{{cite journal |last1=Domingo |first1=E |title=Mechanisms of Viral Emergence |journal=Veterinary Research | year=2010|volume=41 |page=38 |pmid=20167200 |pmc=2831534 |doi=10.1051/vetres/2010010}}</ref> As RNA viruses mutate at extremely high rates, these pathogens are more likely to successfully adapt for invasion of a new host population.<ref name=Woolhouse/>\n\n===Bats===\n[[File: Wikipedia-Bats-001-v01.jpg| 260px|thumb|upright=0.4|left|alt=Different bat species.|Different bat species]]\n\nWhile [[bat]]s are essential members of many ecosystems,<ref name=\"NSF\">{{cite web |last1=National Science Foundation |title=The Night Life: Why We Need Bats All the Time-Not Just on Halloween |url=https://www.nsf.gov/discoveries/disc_summ.jsp?cntn_id=125883 |website=National Science Foundation |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> they are also frequently implicated as the source of emerging virus infections.<ref name=\"Shi2013\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Shi Z |title=Emerging infectious diseases associated with bat viruses |journal=Science China. Life sciences. |volume=56 |issue=8 |pages=678\u201382 |date=2013 |pmid=23917838 |pmc=7088756 |doi=10.1007/s11427-013-4517-x |url=}}</ref> Bats are associated with more zoonotic viruses per host species than any other mammal, and molecular studies have demonstrated that they are the natural hosts for several high-profile zoonotic viruses, including [[severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus]]es and [[Ebola]]/[[Marburg virus disease|Marburg]] hemorrhagic fever filoviruses.<ref name=\"O'Shea\">{{cite journal |last1=O'Shea |first1=TJ |last2=Cryan |first2=PM |last3=Cunningham |first3=AA |last4=Fooks |first4=AR |last5=Hayman |first5=DTS |last6=Luis |first6=AD |last7=Peel |first7=AJ |last8=Plowright |first8=RK |last9=Wood |first9=JLN |title=Bat Flight and Zoonotic Viruses |journal=Emerging Infectious Disease |volume=20(5) |page=741-745 |doi=10.3201/eid2005.130539}}</ref> Viruses can be transmitted from bats via several mechanisms, including bat bite,<ref name=\"Wang2019\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Wang LF, Anderson DE |title=Viruses in bats and potential spillover to animals and humans |journal=Current Opinion in Virology |volume=34 |issue= |pages=79\u201389 |date=2019 |pmid=30665189 |pmc=7102861 |doi=10.1016/j.coviro.2018.12.007 |url=}}</ref> aerosolization of saliva (e.g. during [[animal_echolocation|echolocation]]) and faeces/urine.<ref name=\"Fagre2019\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Fagre AC, Kading RC |title=Can Bats Serve as Reservoirs for Arboviruses? |journal=Viruses |volume=11 |issue=3 |pages= |date=2019 |pmid=30832426 |pmc=6466281 |doi=10.3390/v11030215}}</ref>\n\nDue to their distinct [[ecology]]/behaviour, bats are naturally more susceptible to viral infection and transmission. Several bat species (e.g. brown bats) aggregate in crowded roosts, which promotes intra- and interspecies viral transmission. Moreover, as bats are widespread in urban areas, humans occasionally encroach on their habitats which are contaminated with [[guano]] and urine. Their ability to fly and [[migration (ecology)|migration patterns]] also means that bats are able to spread disease over a large geographic area, while also acquiring new viruses. Additionally, bats experience persistent viral infections which, together with their extreme longevity (some bat species have lifespans of 35 years), helps to maintain viruses and transmit them to other species. Other bat characteristics which contribute to their potency as viral hosts include: their food choices, [[torpor]]/[[hibernation]] habits and susceptibility to reinfection.<ref name=\"Calisher\">{{cite journal |last1=Calisher |first1=CH |last2=Childs |first2= JE|last3=Field |first3=HE |last4=Holmes |first4=KV |last5=Schountz |first5=T |title=Bats: Important Reservoir Hosts of Emerging Viruses |journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews |date=2006 |volume=19(3) |page=531-545 |doi=10.1128/CMR.00017-06}}</ref>\n\n==Drivers of viral emergence==\n{{See also | Infection#Emerging diseases}}\n\nViral emergence is often a consequence of both [[Infection#Emerging diseases|nature and human activity]]. Human [[population growth]] and [[environmental change]]s can greatly facilitate the emergence and re-emergence of zoonotic viruses. Factors such as [[deforestation]], [[reforestation]], [[habitat fragmentation]], [[urbanization]] and [[irrigation]] can all impact the ways in which humans come into close contact with wild animal species, and consequently promote virus emergence.<ref name=\"Nava\">{{cite journal |last1=Nava |first1=A |last2=Shimabukuro |first2=JS |last3=Chmura|first3=AA |last4=Luz|first4=SLB |title=The Impact of Global Environmental Changes on Infectious Disease Emergence with a Focus on Risks for Brazil |journal=ILAR Journal |date=2017 |volume=58 |issue=3 |page=393-400 |url=https://doi.org/10.1093/ilar/ilx034}}</ref> Additionally, [[climate change (general concept)|climate change]] can affect [[ecosystem|ecosystems]] and [[vector]] distribution, which in turn can affect the emergence of [[Vector#Vector-borne zoonotic disease and human activity|vector-borne viruses]]. Other [[ecology|ecological changes]] - for example, species introduction and predator loss - can also affect virus emergence and prevalence. Some [[agriculture|agricultural]] practices, for example inappropriate management and disposal of farm animal faeces, are also associated with an increased risk of zoonosis.<ref name=\"Penakalapati\">{{cite journal |last1=Penakalapati |first1=G |last2=Swarthout |first2=J |last3=Delahoy |first3=MJ |last4=McAliley |first4=L |last5=Wodnik |first5=B |last6=Levy |first6=K |last7=Freeman |first7=MC | title=Exposure to Animal Feces and Human Health: A Systematic Review and Proposed Research Priorities |journal=Environmental Science & Technology |volume=51(20) |page=11537\u201311552 |doi=10.1021/acs.est.7b02811 |pmid=28926696}}</ref>\n\nViruses may also emerge due to the establishment of a larger population that is vulnerable to infection. For example, a virus may emerge following loss of [[cross-reactivity|cross-protective immunity]], which may occur due to loss of a wild virus or termination of [[vaccination]] programmes. Additionally, changes in human [[demography|demographics]] \u2013 for example, the birth and/or migration of immunologically na\u00efve individuals \u2013 can lead to the development of a susceptible population that enables large-scale virus infection. Poor population health (e.g. due to [[HIV]], malnutrition etc) can also facilitate the emergence of viruses.\n\nOther factors that can directly promote viral emergence include [[international trade]] and travel. Animal migration can also lead to the emergence of viruses, as was the case for the [[West Nile virus]] which was spread by migrating bird populations.<ref name=\"Rappole\">{{cite journal |last1=Rappole |first1=JH |last2=Derrickson |first2=SR |last3=Hubalek |first3=Z |title=Migratory birds and spread of West Nile virus in the Western Hemisphere. |journal=Emerging Infectious Disease |date=2000 |volume=6(4) |page=319-28 |doi=10.3201/eid0604.000401}}</ref>\n\n==Virulence of emergent viruses==\n\nAs hosts are immunologically na\u00efve to pathogens they have not encountered before, emergent viruses are often extremely [[virulence|virulent]] in terms of their capacity to cause disease. \n\nTheir high virulence is also due to a lack of adaptation to the new host. Viruses normally exert strong [[evolutionary pressure|selection pressure]] on the immune systems of their natural hosts, which in turn exerts a strong selection pressure on viruses.<ref name=\"Dominguez\">{{cite journal |last1=Dominguez-Andres |first1=J |last2=Netea |first2=MG |title=Impact of Historic Migrations and Evolutionary Processes on Human Immunity |journal=Trends in Immunology |date=2019 |volume=40(12) |page=1105-1119 |url=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.it.2019.10.001}}</ref> This [[coevolution]] means that the natural host is able to manage infection. However, when the virus jumps to a new host (e.g. humans), the new host is unable to deal with infection due to mismatch between host [[wikt:immunoeffector|immunoeffector]]s and virus [[Biological response modifier|immunomodulator]]s. \n\nAdditionally, in order to maximise transmission, viruses often naturally undergo attenuation (i.e. [[virulence]] is reduced) so that infected animals can survive long enough to infect other animals more efficiently.<ref name=\"Longdon\">{{cite journal |last1=Longdon |first1=B |last2=Hadfield |first2=JD |last3=Day |first3=JP |last4=Smith |first4=SCL |last5=McGonigle |first5=JE |last6=Cogni |first6=R |last7=Cao |first7=C |last8=Jiggins |first8=FM |title=The Causes and Consequences of Changes in Virulence following Pathogen Host Shifts |journal=PLoS PATHOGENS |date=2015 |volume=11(3) |doi=10.1371/journal.ppat.1004728 |pmid=25774803}}</ref> However, as attenuation takes a long time to achieve, new host populations will not initially benefit from this phenomenon. Moreover, as zoonotic viruses also naturally exist in [[natural_reservoir|animal reservoirs]]<ref name=Eidson/>, their survival is not dependant on transmission between new hosts; this means that emergent viruses are even more unlikely to attenuate for the purpose of maximal transmission.\n\nAlthough emergent viruses are frequently highly virulent, they are limited by several host factors including: [[innate_immune_system|innate immunity]], [[Antibody#Natural antibodies|natural antibodies]] and [[binding_selectivity|receptor specificity]]. If the host has previously been infected by a pathogen that shares similarities with the emergent virus, the host may also benefit from [[cross-reactivity|cross-protective immunity]].\n\n==Examples of emergent viruses==\n\n===Influenza A===\n[[File: EM of influenza virus.jpg| 210px|thumb|upright=0.4|left|alt=Electron micrograph of influenza virus, magnification is approximately 100,000.|Electron micrograph of influenza virus, magnification is approximately 100,000]]\n\n[[Influenza]] is a [[contagious]] infection which primarily affects the [[respiratory_system|upper respiratory organs]] of humans.<ref name=\"UNICEF\">{{cite web |last1=UNICEF |title=Influenza |url=https://www.unicef.org/flu/ |website=UNICEF |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> Based on their core proteins, influenza viruses are classified into types A, B, C and D.<ref name=\"WHO\">{{cite web |last1=World Health Organisation |title=Influenza |url=https://www.who.int/biologicals/vaccines/influenza/en/ |publisher=World Health Organisation |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> <ref name=\"WHO2\">{{cite web |last1=World Health Organisation |title=Influenza (Avian and other zoonotic) |url=https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/influenza-(avian-and-other-zoonotic) |publisher=WHO |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> While both influenza A and B can cause epidemics in humans, influenza A also has pandemic potential and a higher mutation rate, therefore is most significant to public health.<ref name=\"CDC\">{{cite web |last1=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |title=Influenza (Flu) |url=https://www.cdc.gov/flu/about/viruses/types.htm |publisher=CDC |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=WHO2/>\n\nInfluenza A viruses are further subtyped based on the surface [[glycoprotein]] [[antigens]] [[hemagglutinin]] (HA) and [[neuraminidase]] (NA). The primary natural reservoir for most influenza A subtypes are wild aquatic birds <ref name=WHO2/>; however, through a series of mutations, a small subset of these viruses have adapted for infection of humans (and other animals).<ref name=\"Byrd\">{{cite journal |last1=Byrd-Leotis |first1=L |last2=Byrd-Cummings |first2=RD |last3=Steinhauer |first3=DA |title=The Interplay between the Host Receptor and Influenza Virus Hemagglutinin and Neuraminidase |journal=International Journal of Molecular Sciences |date=2017 |volume=18(7) |page=1541 |doi=10.3390/ijms18071541 |pmid=28714909}}</ref> A key determinant of whether a particular influenza A subtype can infect humans is its binding specificity. Avian influenza A preferentially binds to cell surface receptors with a terminal \u03b12,3\u2010linked sialic acid, while human influenza A preferentially binds to cell surface receptors with a terminal \u03b12,6\u2010linked sialic acid. Via mutation, some avian influenza A viruses have successfully altered their binding specificity from \u03b12,3\u2010 to \u03b12,6\u2010linked sialic acid.<ref name=\"Lewis\">{{cite journal |last1=Lewis |first1=DB |title=Avian Flu to Human Influenza |journal=Annual Review of Medicine |date=2006 |volume=57 |page=139-154 |url=https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev.med.57.121304.131333}}</ref> However, in order to emerge in humans, avian influenza A viruses must also adapt their [[RNA polymerase]]s for function in mammalian cells,<ref name=Long>{{cite journal |last1=Long |first1=JS |last2=Giotis |first2=ES |last3=Moncorg\u00e9 |first3=O |last4=Frise |first4=R |last5=Mistry |first5=B |last6=James |first6=J |last7=Morisson |first7=M |last8=Iqbal |first8=M |last9=Vignal |first9=A |last10=Skinner |first10=MA |last11=Barclay |first11=WS |title=Species difference in ANP32A underlies influenza A virus polymerase host restriction |journal=Nature |date=6 January 2016 |volume=529 |issue=7584 |pages=101\u2013104 |doi=10.1038/nature16474}}</ref> as well as mutating for stability in the acidic respiratory tract of humans.\n\nFollowing [[adaptation]] and [[host switch]], influenza A viruses have the potential to cause epidemics and pandemics in humans. Minor changes in HA and NA structure ([[antigenic drift]]) occur frequently, which enables the virus to cause repetitive outbreaks (i.e. [[flu_season|seasonal influenza]]) by evading immune recognition.<ref name=WHO/> Major changes in HA and NA structure ([[antigenic shift]]), which are caused by genetic reassortment between different influenza A subtypes (e.g. between human and animal subtypes), can instead cause large regional/global [[pandemic|pandemics]].<ref name=WHO/> Due to the emergence of antigenically different influenza A strains in humans, four pandemics emerged in the 20th century alone.<ref name=\"Alexander\">{{cite journal |last1=Alexander |first1=DJ |title=Avian influenza viruses and human health |journal=Developments in Biologicals (Basel) |date=2006 |volume=124 |page=77-84 |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16447497}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, although animal influenza A viruses (e.g. [[avian influenza]], [[swine influenza]]) are distinct from human influenza viruses, they can still cause zoonotic infection in humans. These infections are largely acquired following direct contact with infected animals or contaminated environments, but do not result in efficient human-human transmission; examples of this include [[Influenza_A_virus_subtype_H5N1|H5N1 influenza]] and [[Influenza_A_virus_subtype_H7N9|H7N9 influenza]].<ref name=WHO2/>\n\n===SARS-CoV===\n\n[[File: SARS virion.gif| 200px|thumb|upright=0.4|left|alt=Electron micrograph of SARS-CoV.|Electron micrograph of SARS-CoV]]\n\nIn 2002, a highly pathogenic [[Severe_acute_respiratory_syndrome_coronavirus|SARS-CoV]] strain (Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus) emerged from a zoonotic reservoir; approximately 8000 people were infected worldwide, and mortality rates approached 50% or more in the elderly.<ref name=\"Bolles\">{{cite journal |last1=Bolles |first1=M |last2=Donaldson|first2=E |last3=Baric |first3=R |title=SARS-CoV and emergent coronaviruses: viral determinants of interspecies transmission |journal=Current Opinion in Virology |date=2011 |volume=1(6) |page=624-634 |url=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.coviro.2011.10.012}}</ref> Although SARS-CoV is easily transmitted between humans, this virus is most contagious post-symptoms and therefore the introduction of strict public health measures effectively halted the pandemic.<ref name=Bolles/> The natural reservoir host for SARS-CoV is thought to be [[horseshoe_bat|horseshoe bats]], although the virus has also been identified in several small carnivores (e.g. palm [[civet|civets]] and [[racoon_dog|racoon dogs]]). The emergence of SARS-CoV was believed to have been facilitated by Chinese wet markets, in which civets positive for the virus acted as intermediate hosts and passed SARS-CoV onto humans (and other species).<ref name=Bolles/><ref name=\"Wang\">{{cite journal |last1=Wang |first1=LF |last2=Eaton |first2=BT |title=Bats, civets and the emergence of SARS |journal=Current Topics in Microbiology and Immunology |volume=315 |page=325-44 |doi=10.1007/978-3-540-70962-6_13}}</ref> However, more recent analysis suggests that SARS-CoV may have directly jumped from bats to humans, with subsequent cross-transmission between humans and civets.<ref name=Bolles/> Regarding [[infection]], it was determined that SARS-CoV uses the spike surface [[glycoprotein]] to recognise and bind to host [[Angiotensin-converting enzyme 2|ACE-2]], which it uses as a cellular entry receptor; the development of this characteristic was crucial in enabling SARS-CoV to \u2018jump\u2019 from bats to other species.\n\n===MERS-CoV===\n[[File: MERS-CoV electron micrograph1.jpg| 200px|thumb|upright=0.4|left|alt=Electron micrograph of MERS-CoV.|Electron micrograph of MERS-CoV]]\n\nFirst reported in 2012, [[Middle_East_respiratory_syndrome-related_coronavirus|MERS-CoV]] (Middle East Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus) marks the second known introduction of a highly pathogenic coronavirus from a zoonotic reservoir into humans. The case mortality rate  of this emergent virus is approximately 35%, with 80% of all cases reported by Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"WHO3\">{{cite web |last1=WHO |title=Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) |url=https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/middle-east-respiratory-syndrome-coronavirus-(mers-cov) |website=WHO |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Although MERS-CoV is likely to have originated in bats<ref name=\"Sharif-Yakan\">{{cite journal |last1=Sharif-Yakan |first1=A |last2=Kanj |first2=SS |title=Emergence of MERS-CoV in the Middle East: Origins, Transmission, Treatment, and Perspectives |journal=PLoS PATHOGENS |date=2014 |volume=10(12) |doi=10.1371/journal.ppat.1004457 |pmid=25474536}}</ref>, [[dromedary|dromedary camels]] have been implicated as probable intermediate hosts. MERS-CoV is believed to have been circulating in these mammals for over 20 years, and studies have shown that humans can be infected with MERS-CoV via direct or indirect contact within infected dromedary camels<ref name=WHO3/> - contrastingly, human-human transmission of MERS-CoV is limited.<ref name=WHO3/> \n\nMERS-CoV gains cellular entry by using a spike surface protein to bind to the [[Dipeptidyl_peptidase-4|DPP4]] surface receptor; the core subdomain of this spike surface protein shares similarities with that of SARS-CoV, but its receptor binding subdomain significantly differs.<ref name=Sharif-Yakan/>\n\n===Bluetongue disease===\n[[File:Bluetongue in Captive Yak.gif| 275px|thumb|upright=0.4|left|alt=Domestic [[yak]] with Bluetongue disease - tongue is visibly swollen and cyanotic.| Domestic [[yak]] with Bluetongue disease - tongue is visibly swollen and cyanotic]]\n\n[[Bluetongue disease]] is a [[infectious disease#Contagiousness|non-contagious]] [[vector (epidemiology)|insect-borne]] disease caused by bluetongue virus, which affects species of [[ruminant|ruminants]] (particularly [[sheep]]).<ref name=\"CFSPH\">{{cite web |last1=The Center for Food Security & Public Health |first1=Iowa State University |title=Bluetongue |url=http://www.cfsph.iastate.edu/FastFacts/pdfs/bluetongue_F.pdf |website=CFSPH |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> Climate change has been implicated in the emergence and global spread of this disease, due to its impact on vector distribution. The natural vector of the bluetongue virus is the African midge [[culicoides_imicola|''C. imicola'']], which is normally limited to Africa and subtropical Asia. However, global warming has extended the geographic range of ''C. imicola'', so that it now overlaps with a different vector (''C. pulcaris'' or [[Culicoides obsoletus|''C. obsoletus'']]) with a much more northward geographic range. This change enabled the bluetongue virus to jump vector, thus causing the northward spread of bluetongue disease into Europe.<ref name=\"Purse\">{{cite journal |last1=Purse |first1=BV |last2=Mellor |first2=PS |last3=Rogers |first3=DJ |last4=Samuel |first4=AR |last5=Mertens |first5=PP |last6=Baylis |first6=M |     title=Climate change and the recent emergence of bluetongue in Europe |journal=Nature Reviews Microbiology |volume=3(2) |page=171-81 |doi=10.1038/nrmicro1090}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of emerging infectious diseases]]\n*[[Bushmeat]]\n*[[Viral quasispecies]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.cdc.gov/ncezid/ National Center for Emerging and Zoonotic Infectious Diseases (NCEZID)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070224232126/http://www.microbiologybytes.com/virology/emerging.html MicrobiologyBytes: Emerging Viruses]\n\n{{Infectious disease|state=expanded}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Epidemiology]]\n[[Category:Viruses]]\n[[Category:Zoonoses]]\n[[Category:Virology]]\n", "text_old": "An '''emergent virus''' (or '''emerging virus''') is a [[virus]] that is either newly [[Viral evolution|appeared]], notably increasing in [[incidence (epidemiology)|incidence]]/[[geographic range limit|geographic range]] or has the potential to increase in the near future.<ref name=\"Holland\">{{cite journal |last1=Holland |first1=DJ |title=Emerging Viruses |journal=Current Opinion in Pediatrics |date=1998 |volume=10 |pages=34-40 |pmid=9529635\n|doi=10.1097/00008480-199802000-00007}}</ref> Emergent viruses are a leading cause of [[emerging infectious disease]]s and raise [[public health]] challenges globally, given their potential to cause [[disease outbreak|outbreak]]s of disease which can sometimes lead to [[epidemic]]s and [[pandemic]]s.<ref name=\"Devaux2012\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Devaux CA |title=Emerging and re-emerging viruses: A global challenge illustrated by Chikungunya virus outbreaks |journal=World J Virol |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=11\u201322 |date=2012 |pmid=24175207 |pmc=3782263 |doi=10.5501/wjv.v1.i1.11 |url=}}</ref> Recent examples include the [[SARS-related coronavirus]]es, which have caused the [[2002-2004 SARS outbreak|2002-2004 outbreak]] of [[severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] ([[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus|SARS-CoV-1]]) and the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] ([[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]).<ref name=\"Zheng2020\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Zheng J |title=SARS-CoV-2: an Emerging Coronavirus that Causes a Global Threat |journal=International Journal of Biological Sciences |volume=16 |issue=10 |pages=1678\u201385 |date=2020 |pmid=32226285 |pmc=7098030 |doi=10.7150/ijbs.45053 |url=}}</ref> Other examples include the [[human immunodeficiency virus]] which causes [[HIV/AIDS]]; the viruses responsible for [[Ebola]];<ref name=\"Holmes2016\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Holmes EC, Dudas G, Rambaut A, Andersen KG |title=The evolution of Ebola virus: Insights from the 2013-2016 epidemic |journal=Nature |volume=538 |issue=7624 |pages=193\u2013200 |date=2016 |pmid=27734858 |pmc=5580494 |doi=10.1038/nature19790 |url=}}</ref> the [[H5N1]] influenza virus responsible for [[avian flu]];<ref name=\"Wei2016\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Wei P, Cai Z, Hua J, et al. |title=Pains and Gains from China's Experiences with Emerging Epidemics: From SARS to H7N9 |journal=Biomed Res Int |volume=2016 |issue= |pages=5717108 |date=2016 |pmid=27525272 |pmc=4971293 |doi=10.1155/2016/5717108 |url=}}</ref> and [[H1N1/09]], which caused the [[2009 swine flu]] pandemic.<ref name=\"Smith2009\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Smith GJ, Vijaykrishna D, Bahl J, et al. |title=Origins and evolutionary genomics of the 2009 swine-origin H1N1 influenza A epidemic |journal=Nature |volume=459 |issue=7250 |pages=1122\u20135 |date=2009 |pmid=19516283 |doi=10.1038/nature08182 |url=}}</ref> An earlier emergent [[Viral strain|strain]] of [[H1N1]] caused the 1918 [[Spanish flu]] pandemic.<ref name=\"Taubenberger2006\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Taubenberger JK, Morens DM |title=1918 Influenza: the mother of all pandemics |journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=15\u201322 |date=2006 |pmid=16494711 |pmc=3291398 |doi=10.3201/eid1201.050979}}</ref> The most frequent cause of viral emergence in humans is [[zoonosis]], which involves a [[Cross-species transmission|cross-species jump]] of a [[viral disease]] into humans from other animals. As zoonotic viruses exist in [[Natural reservoir|animal reservoir]]s, they are much more difficult to [[eradication of infectious diseases|eradicate]] and can therefore establish persistent infections in human populations.<ref name=\"Eidson\">{{cite web |last1=Eidson |first1=M |title=Zoonotic disease |url=https://www.britannica.com/science/zoonotic-disease |publisher=Britannica |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nEmergent viruses should not be confused with '''re-emerging viruses''' and '''newly-detected viruses'''. A re-emerging virus is generally considered to be a previously appeared virus that is experiencing a resurgence<ref name=\"Holland\"/><ref name=\"Porta2008\">{{cite book |editor=Miquel Porta |title=A Dictionary of Epidemiology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3Dr8dyuzvTkC |year=2008 |publisher=Oxford University Press, USA |isbn=978-0-19-971815-3 |page=78}}</ref> - for example, [[measles]] is re-emerging as a serious public health threat, with outbreaks occurring in even highly developed countries.<ref name=\"Poland\">{{cite journal |last1=Poland |first1=GA |last2=Jacobson |first2=RM |title=The Re-Emergence of Measles in Developed Countries: Time to Develop the Next-Generation Measles Vaccines? |journal=Vaccine |date=2012 |volume=30(2) |page=103-4 |doi=10.1016/j.vaccine.2011.11.085 |pmid=22196079}}</ref> A newly-detected virus is a previously unrecognized virus that had been circulating in the species as [[endemic (epidemiology)|endemic]] or epidemic infections.<ref name=\"Woolhouse2\">{{cite journal |last1=Woolhouse |first1=M |last2=Scott |first2=F |last3=Hudson |first3=Z |last4=Howey |first4=R |last5=Chase-Topping |first5=M |title=Human viruses: discovery and emergence |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society London B Biological Science |date=2012 |volume=367(1604) |doi=10.1098/rstb.2011.0354 |pmid=22966141}}</ref> Newly-detected viruses may have escaped [[Virus classification|classification]] because they left no distinctive [[Disease surveillance|clues]], and/or could not be isolated or propagated in [[Viral culture|cell culture]].<ref name=\"Leland\">{{cite journal |last1=Leland |first1=DS |last2=Ginocchio |first2=CC |title=Role of Cell Culture for Virus Detection in the Age of Technology |journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews |date=2007 |volume=20(1) |doi=10.1128/CMR.00002-06 |pmid=17223623}}</ref> Examples include [[rhinovirus|human rhinovirus]] (a leading cause of common colds which was first identified in 1956),<ref name=Kennedy2012>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kennedy JL, Turner RB, Braciale T, Heymann PW, Borish L |title=Pathogenesis of rhinovirus infection |journal=Current Opinion in Virology |volume=2 |issue=3 |pages=287\u201393 |date=2012 |pmid=22542099 |pmc=3378761 |doi=10.1016/j.coviro.2012.03.008}}</ref> [[hepatitis C]] (eventually identified in 1989),<ref name=Houghton>{{cite journal |vauthors=Houghton M | authorlink=Michael Houghton (virologist) |title=The long and winding road leading to the identification of the hepatitis C virus |journal=Journal of Hepatology |volume=51 |issue=5 |pages=939\u201348 |date=2009 |pmid=19781804 |doi=10.1016/j.jhep.2009.08.004 |url=http://www.journal-of-hepatology.eu/article/S0168-8278%2809%2900535-2/fulltext}}</ref>  and [[human metapneumovirus]] (first described in 2001, but thought to have been circulating since the 19th century).<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=de Graaf M, Osterhaus AD, Fouchier RA, Holmes EC |title=Evolutionary dynamics of human and avian metapneumoviruses |journal=The Journal of General Virology |volume=89  |issue=12 |pages=2933\u20132942 |date=2008 |pmid=19008378 |doi=10.1099/vir.0.2008/006957-0 |url=}}</ref> As the detection of such viruses is technology driven, the number reported is likely to expand.\n\n==Zoonosis==\n{{See also|Zoonosis}}\nGiven the rarity of spontaneous development of new virus species, the most frequent cause of emergent viruses in humans is [[zoonosis]]. This phenomenon is estimated to account for 73% of all [[Emerging infectious disease|emerging or re-emerging pathogens]], with viruses playing a disproportionately large role.<ref name=\"Woolhouse\"/> [[RNA virus]]es are particularly frequent, accounting for 37% of emerging and re-emerging pathogens.<ref name=\"Woolhouse\">{{cite journal |last1=Woolhouse |first1=ME | authorlink=Mark Woolhouse | last2=Gowtage-Sequeria |first2=S| title=Host Range and Emerging and Reemerging Pathogens |journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases |date=2005 |volume=11 |page=1842-7 |pmid=16485468 |pmc=3367654 |doi=10.3201/eid1112.050997}}</ref> A broad range of animals - including wild birds, rodents and bats - are associated with zoonotic viruses.<ref name=\"Kruse\">{{cite journal |last1=Kruse |first1=H |last2=Kirkemo|first2=A |last3=Handeland |first3=K |title=Wildlife as Source of Zoonotic Infections |journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases |date=2004 |volume=10(12) |page=2067-2072 |doi=10.3201/eid1012.040707 |pmid=15663840 |pmc=3323390}}</ref> It is not possible to predict specific zoonotic events that may be associated with a particular animal reservoir at any given time.<ref name=\"Domingo\"/>\n\n[[Spillover infection|Zoonotic spillover]] can either result in self-limited infections, in which no further human-human transmission occurs (as with the [[rabies|rabies virus]]), or in infectious cases, in which the zoonotic pathogen is able to sustain human-human transmission (as with the [[Ebola|Ebola virus]]). If the zoonotic virus is able to maintain successful human-human transmission, an [[Disease outbreak|outbreak]] may occur.<ref name=Parrish>{{cite journal | last1 = Parrish | first1 = CR | last2 = Holmes | first2 = EC | last3 = Morens | first3 = DM | display-authors = etal | title = Cross-Species Virus Transmission and the Emergence of New Epidemic Diseases | journal = Microbiology and Molecular Biology Reviews | volume = 72 | issue = 3 | pages = 457\u2013470 | date = 2008 | doi =10.1128/MMBR.00004-08 | pmid=18772285 | pmc=2546865}}</ref> Some spillover events can also result in the virus adapting exclusively for human infection (as occurred with the [[HIV|HIV virus]]), in which case humans become a new reservoir for the pathogen.\n\nA successful zoonotic 'jump' depends on human contact with an animal harbouring a virus variant that is able to infect humans. A virus originating from an animal reservoir will normally undergo [[mutation]], [[genetic recombination]] and [[reassortment]] so as to allow it to extend its [[host range|range of infectable species]] to include humans, and to sustain efficient human-human transmission.<ref name=\"Domingo\">{{cite journal |last1=Domingo |first1=E |title=Mechanisms of Viral Emergence |journal=Veterinary Research | year=2010|volume=41 |page=38 |pmid=20167200 |pmc=2831534 |doi=10.1051/vetres/2010010}}</ref> As RNA viruses mutate at extremely high rates, these pathogens are more likely to successfully adapt for invasion of a new host population.<ref name=Woolhouse/>\n\n===Bats===\n[[File: Wikipedia-Bats-001-v01.jpg| 260px|thumb|upright=0.4|left|alt=Different bat species.|Different bat species]]\n\nWhile [[bat]]s are essential members of many ecosystems,<ref name=\"NSF\">{{cite web |last1=National Science Foundation |title=The Night Life: Why We Need Bats All the Time-Not Just on Halloween |url=https://www.nsf.gov/discoveries/disc_summ.jsp?cntn_id=125883 |website=National Science Foundation |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> they are also frequently implicated as the source of emerging virus infections.<ref name=\"Shi2013\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Shi Z |title=Emerging infectious diseases associated with bat viruses |journal=Science China. Life sciences. |volume=56 |issue=8 |pages=678\u201382 |date=2013 |pmid=23917838 |pmc=7088756 |doi=10.1007/s11427-013-4517-x |url=}}</ref> Bats are associated with more zoonotic viruses per host species than any other mammal, and molecular studies have demonstrated that they are the natural hosts for several high-profile zoonotic viruses, including [[severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus]]es and [[Ebola]]/[[Marburg virus disease|Marburg]] hemorrhagic fever filoviruses.<ref name=\"O'Shea\">{{cite journal |last1=O'Shea |first1=TJ |last2=Cryan |first2=PM |last3=Cunningham |first3=AA |last4=Fooks |first4=AR |last5=Hayman |first5=DTS |last6=Luis |first6=AD |last7=Peel |first7=AJ |last8=Plowright |first8=RK |last9=Wood |first9=JLN |title=Bat Flight and Zoonotic Viruses |journal=Emerging Infectious Disease |volume=20(5) |page=741-745 |doi=10.3201/eid2005.130539}}</ref> Viruses can be transmitted from bats via several mechanisms, including bat bite,<ref name=\"Wang2019\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Wang LF, Anderson DE |title=Viruses in bats and potential spillover to animals and humans |journal=Current Opinion in Virology |volume=34 |issue= |pages=79\u201389 |date=2019 |pmid=30665189 |pmc=7102861 |doi=10.1016/j.coviro.2018.12.007 |url=}}</ref> aerosolization of saliva (e.g. during [[animal_echolocation|echolocation]]) and faeces/urine.<ref name=\"Fagre2019\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Fagre AC, Kading RC |title=Can Bats Serve as Reservoirs for Arboviruses? |journal=Viruses |volume=11 |issue=3 |pages= |date=2019 |pmid=30832426 |pmc=6466281 |doi=10.3390/v11030215}}</ref>\n\nDue to their distinct [[ecology]]/behaviour, bats are naturally more susceptible to viral infection and transmission. Several bat species (e.g. brown bats) aggregate in crowded roosts, which promotes intra- and interspecies viral transmission. Moreover, as bats are widespread in urban areas, humans occasionally encroach on their habitats which are contaminated with [[guano]] and urine. Their ability to fly and [[migration (ecology)|migration patterns]] also means that bats are able to spread disease over a large geographic area, while also acquiring new viruses. Additionally, bats experience persistent viral infections which, together with their extreme longevity (some bat species have lifespans of 35 years), helps to maintain viruses and transmit them to other species. Other bat characteristics which contribute to their potency as viral hosts include: their food choices, [[torpor]]/[[hibernation]] habits and susceptibility to reinfection.<ref name=\"Calisher\">{{cite journal |last1=Calisher |first1=CH |last2=Childs |first2= JE|last3=Field |first3=HE |last4=Holmes |first4=KV |last5=Schountz |first5=T |title=Bats: Important Reservoir Hosts of Emerging Viruses |journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews |date=2006 |volume=19(3) |page=531-545 |doi=10.1128/CMR.00017-06}}</ref>\n\n==Drivers of viral emergence==\n{{See also | Infection#Emerging diseases}}\n\nViral emergence is often a consequence of both [[Infection#Emerging diseases|nature and human activity]]. Human [[population growth]] and [[environmental change]]s can greatly facilitate the emergence and re-emergence of zoonotic viruses. Factors such as [[deforestation]], [[reforestation]], [[habitat fragmentation]], [[urbanization]] and [[irrigation]] can all impact the ways in which humans come into close contact with wild animal species, and consequently promote virus emergence.<ref name=\"Nava\">{{cite journal |last1=Nava |first1=A |last2=Shimabukuro |first2=JS |last3=Chmura|first3=AA |last4=Luz|first4=SLB |title=The Impact of Global Environmental Changes on Infectious Disease Emergence with a Focus on Risks for Brazil |journal=ILAR Journal |date=2017 |volume=58 |issue=3 |page=393-400 |url=https://doi.org/10.1093/ilar/ilx034}}</ref> Additionally, [[climate change (general concept)|climate change]] can affect [[ecosystem|ecosystems]] and [[vector]] distribution, which in turn can affect the emergence of [[Vector#Vector-borne zoonotic disease and human activity|vector-borne viruses]]. Other [[ecology|ecological changes]] - for example, species introduction and predator loss - can also affect virus emergence and prevalence. Some [[agriculture|agricultural]] practices, for example inappropriate management and disposal of farm animal faeces, are also associated with an increased risk of zoonosis.<ref name=\"Penakalapati\">{{cite journal |last1=Penakalapati |first1=G |last2=Swarthout |first2=J |last3=Delahoy |first3=MJ |last4=McAliley |first4=L |last5=Wodnik |first5=B |last6=Levy |first6=K |last7=Freeman |first7=MC | title=Exposure to Animal Feces and Human Health: A Systematic Review and Proposed Research Priorities |journal=Environmental Science & Technology |volume=51(20) |page=11537\u201311552 |doi=10.1021/acs.est.7b02811 |pmid=28926696}}</ref>\n\nViruses may also emerge due to the establishment of a larger population that is vulnerable to infection. For example, a virus may emerge following loss of [[cross-reactivity|cross-protective immunity]], which may occur due to loss of a wild virus or termination of [[vaccination]] programmes. Additionally, changes in human [[demography|demographics]] \u2013 for example, the birth and/or migration of immunologically na\u00efve individuals \u2013 can lead to the development of a susceptible population that enables large-scale virus infection. Poor population health (e.g. due to [[HIV]], malnutrition etc) can also facilitate the emergence of viruses.\n\nOther factors that can directly promote viral emergence include [[international trade]] and travel. Animal migration can also lead to the emergence of viruses, as was the case for the [[West Nile virus]] which was spread by migrating bird populations.<ref name=\"Rappole\">{{cite journal |last1=Rappole |first1=JH |last2=Derrickson |first2=SR |last3=Hubalek |first3=Z |title=Migratory birds and spread of West Nile virus in the Western Hemisphere. |journal=Emerging Infectious Disease |date=2000 |volume=6(4) |page=319-28 |doi=10.3201/eid0604.000401}}</ref>\n\n==Virulence of emergent viruses==\n\nAs hosts are immunologically na\u00efve to pathogens they have not encountered before, emergent viruses are often extremely [[virulence|virulent]] in terms of their capacity to cause disease. \n\nTheir high virulence is also due to a lack of adaptation to the new host. Viruses normally exert strong [[evolutionary pressure|selection pressure]] on the immune systems of their natural hosts, which in turn exerts a strong selection pressure on viruses.<ref name=\"Dominguez\">{{cite journal |last1=Dominguez-Andres |first1=J |last2=Netea |first2=MG |title=Impact of Historic Migrations and Evolutionary Processes on Human Immunity |journal=Trends in Immunology |date=2019 |volume=40(12) |page=1105-1119 |url=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.it.2019.10.001}}</ref> This [[coevolution]] means that the natural host is able to manage infection. However, when the virus jumps to a new host (e.g. humans), the new host is unable to deal with infection due to mismatch between host [[wikt:immunoeffector|immunoeffector]]s and virus [[Biological response modifier|immunomodulator]]s. \n\nAdditionally, in order to maximise transmission, viruses often naturally undergo attenuation (i.e. [[virulence]] is reduced) so that infected animals can survive long enough to infect other animals more efficiently.<ref name=\"Longdon\">{{cite journal |last1=Longdon |first1=B |last2=Hadfield |first2=JD |last3=Day |first3=JP |last4=Smith |first4=SCL |last5=McGonigle |first5=JE |last6=Cogni |first6=R |last7=Cao |first7=C |last8=Jiggins |first8=FM |title=The Causes and Consequences of Changes in Virulence following Pathogen Host Shifts |journal=PLoS PATHOGENS |date=2015 |volume=11(3) |doi=10.1371/journal.ppat.1004728 |pmid=25774803}}</ref> However, as attenuation takes a long time to achieve, new host populations will not initially benefit from this phenomenon. Moreover, as zoonotic viruses also naturally exist in [[natural_reservoir|animal reservoirs]]<ref name=Eidson/>, their survival is not dependant on transmission between new hosts; this means that emergent viruses are even more unlikely to attenuate for the purpose of maximal transmission.\n\nAlthough emergent viruses are frequently highly virulent, they are limited by several host factors including: [[innate_immune_system|innate immunity]], [[Antibody#Natural antibodies|natural antibodies]] and [[binding_selectivity|receptor specificity]]. If the host has previously been infected by a pathogen that shares similarities with the emergent virus, the host may also benefit from [[cross-reactivity|cross-protective immunity]].\n\n==Examples of emergent viruses==\n\n===Influenza A===\n[[File: EM of influenza virus.jpg| 210px|thumb|upright=0.4|left|alt=Electron micrograph of influenza virus, magnification is approximately 100,000.|Electron micrograph of influenza virus, magnification is approximately 100,000]]\n\n[[Influenza]] is a [[contagious]] infection which primarily affects the [[respiratory_system|upper respiratory organs]] of humans.<ref name=\"UNICEF\">{{cite web |last1=UNICEF |title=Influenza |url=https://www.unicef.org/flu/ |website=UNICEF |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> Based on their core proteins, influenza viruses are classified into types A, B, C and D.<ref name=\"WHO\">{{cite web |last1=World Health Organisation |title=Influenza |url=https://www.who.int/biologicals/vaccines/influenza/en/ |publisher=World Health Organisation |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> <ref name=\"WHO2\">{{cite web |last1=World Health Organisation |title=Influenza (Avian and other zoonotic) |url=https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/influenza-(avian-and-other-zoonotic) |publisher=WHO |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> While both influenza A and B can cause epidemics in humans, influenza A also has pandemic potential and a higher mutation rate, therefore is most significant to public health.<ref name=\"CDC\">{{cite web |last1=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |title=Influenza (Flu) |url=https://www.cdc.gov/flu/about/viruses/types.htm |publisher=CDC |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=WHO2/>\n\nInfluenza A viruses are further subtyped based on the surface [[glycoprotein]] [[antigens]] [[hemagglutinin]] (HA) and [[neuraminidase]] (NA). The primary natural reservoir for most influenza A subtypes are wild aquatic birds <ref name=WHO2/>; however, through a series of mutations, a small subset of these viruses have adapted for infection of humans (and other animals).<ref name=\"Byrd\">{{cite journal |last1=Byrd-Leotis |first1=L |last2=Byrd-Cummings |first2=RD |last3=Steinhauer |first3=DA |title=The Interplay between the Host Receptor and Influenza Virus Hemagglutinin and Neuraminidase |journal=International Journal of Molecular Sciences |date=2017 |volume=18(7) |page=1541 |doi=10.3390/ijms18071541 |pmid=28714909}}</ref> A key determinant of whether a particular influenza A subtype can infect humans is its binding specificity. Avian influenza A preferentially binds to cell surface receptors with a terminal \u03b12,3\u2010linked sialic acid, while human influenza A preferentially binds to cell surface receptors with a terminal \u03b12,6\u2010linked sialic acid. Via mutation, some avian influenza A viruses have successfully altered their binding specificity from \u03b12,3\u2010 to \u03b12,6\u2010linked sialic acid.<ref name=\"Lewis\">{{cite journal |last1=Lewis |first1=DB |title=Avian Flu to Human Influenza |journal=Annual Review of Medicine |date=2006 |volume=57 |page=139-154 |url=https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev.med.57.121304.131333}}</ref> However, in order to emerge in humans, avian influenza A viruses must also adapt their [[RNA polymerase]]s for function in mammalian cells,<ref name=Long>{{cite journal |last1=Long |first1=JS |last2=Giotis |first2=ES |last3=Moncorg\u00e9 |first3=O |last4=Frise |first4=R |last5=Mistry |first5=B |last6=James |first6=J |last7=Morisson |first7=M |last8=Iqbal |first8=M |last9=Vignal |first9=A |last10=Skinner |first10=MA |last11=Barclay |first11=WS |title=Species difference in ANP32A underlies influenza A virus polymerase host restriction |journal=Nature |date=6 January 2016 |volume=529 |issue=7584 |pages=101\u2013104 |doi=10.1038/nature16474}}</ref> as well as mutating for stability in the acidic respiratory tract of humans.\n\nFollowing [[adaptation]] and [[host switch]], influenza A viruses have the potential to cause epidemics and pandemics in humans. Minor changes in HA and NA structure ([[antigenic drift]]) occur frequently, which enables the virus to cause repetitive outbreaks (i.e. [[flu_season|seasonal influenza]]) by evading immune recognition.<ref name=WHO/> Major changes in HA and NA structure ([[antigenic shift]]), which are caused by genetic reassortment between different influenza A subtypes (e.g. between human and animal subtypes), can instead cause large regional/global [[pandemic|pandemics]].<ref name=WHO/> Due to the emergence of antigenically different influenza A strains in humans, four pandemics emerged in the 20th century alone.<ref name=\"Alexander\">{{cite journal |last1=Alexander |first1=DJ |title=Avian influenza viruses and human health |journal=Developments in Biologicals (Basel) |date=2006 |volume=124 |page=77-84 |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16447497}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, although animal influenza A viruses (e.g. [[avian influenza]], [[swine influenza]]) are distinct from human influenza viruses, they can still cause zoonotic infection in humans. These infections are largely acquired following direct contact with infected animals or contaminated environments, but do not result in efficient human-human transmission; examples of this include [[Influenza_A_virus_subtype_H5N1|H5N1 influenza]] and [[Influenza_A_virus_subtype_H7N9|H7N9 influenza]].<ref name=WHO2/>\n\n===SARS-CoV===\n\n[[File: SARS virion.gif| 200px|thumb|upright=0.4|left|alt=Electron micrograph of SARS-CoV.|Electron micrograph of SARS-CoV]]\n\nIn 2002, a highly pathogenic [[Severe_acute_respiratory_syndrome_coronavirus|SARS-CoV]] strain (Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus) emerged from a zoonotic reservoir; approximately 8000 people were infected worldwide, and mortality rates approached 50% or more in the elderly.<ref name=\"Bolles\">{{cite journal |last1=Bolles |first1=M |last2=Donaldson|first2=E |last3=Baric |first3=R |title=SARS-CoV and emergent coronaviruses: viral determinants of interspecies transmission |journal=Current Opinion in Virology |date=2011 |volume=1(6) |page=624-634 |url=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.coviro.2011.10.012}}</ref> Although SARS-CoV is easily transmitted between humans, this virus is most contagious post-symptoms and therefore the introduction of strict public health measures effectively halted the pandemic.<ref name=Bolles/> The natural reservoir host for SARS-CoV is thought to be [[horseshoe_bat|horseshoe bats]], although the virus has also been identified in several small carnivores (e.g. palm [[civet|civets]] and [[racoon_dog|racoon dogs]]). The emergence of SARS-CoV was believed to have been facilitated by Chinese wet markets, in which civets positive for the virus acted as intermediate hosts and passed SARS-CoV onto humans (and other species).<ref name=Bolles/><ref name=\"Wang\">{{cite journal |last1=Wang |first1=LF |last2=Eaton |first2=BT |title=Bats, civets and the emergence of SARS |journal=Current Topics in Microbiology and Immunology |volume=315 |page=325-44 |doi=10.1007/978-3-540-70962-6_13}}</ref> However, more recent analysis suggests that SARS-CoV may have directly jumped from bats to humans, with subsequent cross-transmission between humans and civets.<ref name=Bolles/> Regarding [[infection]], it was determined that SARS-CoV uses the spike surface [[glycoprotein]] to recognise and bind to host [[Angiotensin-converting enzyme 2|ACE-2]], which it uses as a cellular entry receptor; the development of this characteristic was crucial in enabling SARS-CoV to \u2018jump\u2019 from bats to other species.\n\n===MERS-CoV===\n[[File: MERS-CoV electron micrograph1.jpg| 200px|thumb|upright=0.4|left|alt=Electron micrograph of MERS-CoV.|Electron micrograph of MERS-CoV]]\n\nFirst reported in 2012, [[Middle_East_respiratory_syndrome-related_coronavirus|MERS-CoV]] (Middle East Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus) marks the second known introduction of a highly pathogenic coronavirus from a zoonotic reservoir into humans. The case mortality rate  of this emergent virus is approximately 35%, with 80% of all cases reported by Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"WHO3\">{{cite web |last1=WHO |title=Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) |url=https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/middle-east-respiratory-syndrome-coronavirus-(mers-cov) |website=WHO |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Although MERS-CoV is likely to have originated in bats<ref name=\"Sharif-Yakan\">{{cite journal |last1=Sharif-Yakan |first1=A |last2=Kanj |first2=SS |title=Emergence of MERS-CoV in the Middle East: Origins, Transmission, Treatment, and Perspectives |journal=PLoS PATHOGENS |date=2014 |volume=10(12) |doi=10.1371/journal.ppat.1004457 |pmid=25474536}}</ref>, [[dromedary|dromedary camels]] have been implicated as probable intermediate hosts. MERS-CoV is believed to have been circulating in these mammals for over 20 years, and studies have shown that humans can be infected with MERS-CoV via direct or indirect contact within infected dromedary camels<ref name=WHO3/> - contrastingly, human-human transmission of MERS-CoV is limited.<ref name=WHO3/> \n\nMERS-CoV gains cellular entry by using a spike surface protein to bind to the [[Dipeptidyl_peptidase-4|DPP4]] surface receptor; the core subdomain of this spike surface protein shares similarities with that of SARS-CoV, but its receptor binding subdomain significantly differs.<ref name=Sharif-Yakan/>\n\n===Bluetongue disease===\n[[File:Bluetongue in Captive Yak.gif| 275px|thumb|upright=0.4|left|alt=Domestic [[yak]] with Bluetongue disease - tongue is visibly swollen and cyanotic.| Domestic [[yak]] with Bluetongue disease - tongue is visibly swollen and cyanotic]]\n\n[[Bluetongue disease]] is a [[infectious disease#Contagiousness|non-contagious]] [[vector (epidemiology)|insect-borne]] disease caused by bluetongue virus, which affects species of [[ruminant|ruminants]] (particularly [[sheep]]).<ref name=\"CFSPH\">{{cite web |last1=The Center for Food Security & Public Health |first1=Iowa State University |title=Bluetongue |url=http://www.cfsph.iastate.edu/FastFacts/pdfs/bluetongue_F.pdf |website=CFSPH |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> Climate change has been implicated in the emergence and global spread of this disease, due to its impact on vector distribution. The natural vector of the bluetongue virus is the African midge [[culicoides_imicola|''C. imicola'']], which is normally limited to Africa and subtropical Asia. However, global warming has extended the geographic range of ''C. imicola'', so that it now overlaps with a different vector (''C. pulcaris'' or [[Culicoides obsoletus|''C. obsoletus'']]) with a much more northward geographic range. This change enabled the bluetongue virus to jump vector, thus causing the northward spread of bluetongue disease into Europe.<ref name=\"Purse\">{{cite journal |last1=Purse |first1=BV |last2=Mellor |first2=PS |last3=Rogers |first3=DJ |last4=Samuel |first4=AR |last5=Mertens |first5=PP |last6=Baylis |first6=M |     title=Climate change and the recent emergence of bluetongue in Europe |journal=Nature Reviews Microbiology |volume=3(2) |page=171-81 |doi=10.1038/nrmicro1090}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of emerging infectious diseases]]\n*[[Bushmeat]]\n*[[Viral quasispecies]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.cdc.gov/ncezid/ National Center for Emerging and Zoonotic Infectious Diseases (NCEZID)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070224232126/http://www.microbiologybytes.com/virology/emerging.html MicrobiologyBytes: Emerging Viruses]\n\n{{Infectious disease|state=expanded}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Epidemiology]]\n[[Category:Viruses]]\n[[Category:Zoonoses]]\n[[Category:Virology]]\n", "name_user": "Aida Getachew", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emergent_virus"}
{"title_page": "Texas country music", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Original research|date=November 2009}}\n{{Essay-like|date=November 2009}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2019}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox music genre\n|name=Texas country music \n|bgcolor=brown\n|color=white\n|stylistic_origins={{hlist|[[Country music|Country]]|[[Western music (North America)|Western]]|[[outlaw country]]}}\n|cultural_origins=Late 1960s, [[Texas]], United States\n|instruments={{hlist|[[Acoustic guitar]]|[[electric guitar]]|[[steel guitar]]|[[bass guitar]]|[[percussion]]|[[banjo]]|[[mandolin]]|[[Dobro]]|[[fiddle]]|[[piano]]|[[harmonica]]}}\n|popularity=[[Texas]]\n|derivatives={{hlist|[[Neotraditional country]]\n|[[progressive country]]\n|[[Red Dirt (music)|Red Dirt]]}}}}\n\n'''Texas Country Music''' (more popularly known just as '''Texas Country''' or '''Texas Music''') is a rapidly growing subgenre of [[country music]] from [[Texas]]. Texas country is a unique style of [[Western music (North America)|Western music]] and is often associated with other distinct neighboring styles,<ref name=\"Galit Simmons 2005 p. 68\">{{cite book | last=Galit | first=E.L. | last2=Simmons | first2=V. | title=Exploring Texas History: Weekend Adventures | publisher=Taylor Trade Publishing | year=2005 | isbn=978-1-58979-202-9 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=poDYKu4UHjAC&pg=PA68 | language=nl | access-date=2020-04-12 | page=68}}</ref> including [[Red Dirt (music)|Red Dirt]] from [[Oklahoma]],<ref name=\"Semer p. 3\">{{cite book | last=Semer | first=A. | title=T is For Texas | isbn=978-1-387-78328-1 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zIVaDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA3 | access-date=2020-04-12 | page=3}}</ref> the [[New Mexico music]] of [[New Mexico]],<ref name=\"Billboard p. 49\">{{cite book | title=Billboard | publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc. | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RAkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT49 | language=de | access-date=2020-04-12 | page=49}}</ref> and [[Tejano music|Tejano]] in [[West Texas]].<ref name=\"Jasinski Monahan 2012 p. 553\">{{cite book | last=Jasinski | first=L.E. | last2=Monahan | first2=C. | title=Handbook of Texas Music | publisher=Texas State Historical Assn | year=2012 | isbn=978-0-87611-297-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CE8xiT3pV6QC&pg=PT553 | access-date=2020-04-12 | page=553}}</ref> All of which have influenced one another over the years, and are popular throughout Texas, the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]], the  [[Southwestern United States|Southwest]], and other parts of the [[Western United States]]. Texas Country is known for fusing [[Neotraditional country|neotraditional country]] with the outspoken, care-free views of [[outlaw country]]. Texas Country blends these sub-genres with a [[common people|\"common working man\"]] theme and witty undertones, these often combine with a stripped down music sound.\n\nNeither the location of birth nor the location of upbringing seems to calculate in the definition of a Texas Country artist, as long as the origin is not in the corporate Nashville scene as the genre tends to be anti-Nashville. The genre differentiates from Nashville country with its rejection of pop influences that is found in Nashville Country recently, but does not necessarily mean the artist/group is Texas based.  For example, [[Chris Knight (musician)|Chris Knight]] is considered by some to be a Texas Country musician, despite his [[Kentucky]] ties. [[Adam Hood]], an [[Alabama]] native, also has had success in the genre. Even international musicians, such as [[Alberta, Canada]] native [[Corb Lund]], have been successful in the Texas Country scene. This just shows how many musicians all over the world have adopted the Texas sound.\n\n==Instrumentation==\n{{unsourced section|date=July 2019}}\nThe [[Steel-string guitar|acoustic guitar]] is essential in Texas Country Music. However, the use of [[electric guitar]]s, [[steel guitar]]s or [[pedal steel guitar]]s in the genre is not uncommon. [[bass guitar|Bass]] and [[percussion]] are used in live performances. The sounds of [[piano]], [[baritone guitar]], [[banjo]], [[accordion]], [[fiddle]] or [[harmonica]] on studio recordings are the norm for the genre.\n\n==Vocals==\nThe line of delineation for vocals is unclear. Traditionally, the Texas Country scene has been a male dominated genre, however many women have had chart success in recent years. The Texas \"anthem\" is a common song type, referencing and sometimes embellishing on the different positive characteristics of the state. Many of these types of songs have been popular on the Texas Music Charts.<ref>[http://www.countryradioclassics.com/index.php/2007/09/21/texas-national-anthem-voting/ TX National Anthem voting ] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080703153140/http://www.countryradioclassics.com/index.php/2007/09/21/texas-national-anthem-voting |date=2008-07-03 }} (sponsored by Lone-Star Beer company)</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\nThe live performance is at the very root of the Texas Country scene.  Enthusiasm is the best descriptor for both band and crowd at a live Texas Country performance. \"It is not an uncommon sight to see clubs all over Texas packed to the rafters; girls and boys in cowboy hats and [[Wrangler Jeans|Wranglers]] [[Country-western two-step|two-step]]ping next to the mosh pit, where [[frat boy|college boys or \"Man Fans\"]] in khakis and college girls pressed up against the stage\".<ref>Lone Star Music. Kevin Fowler Biography. [http://www.lonestarmusic.com/biography.asp?id=86 November 9, 2006] LoneStar Music.</ref> An important factor Texas Country's success is in the frequency of live performances. It is not uncommon for a Texas Country band to tour 200+ dates a year, all, or nearly all, in the State of Texas{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}. This allows the fan to attend a band's show more often, thus interacting with the music on a more personal level.\nPopular venues include, [[Gruene Hall]] (Gruene), [[Billy Bob's]] (Ft. Worth), [http://www.cowboysdancehall.com/dallas/ Cowboys Red River]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cowboysdancehall.com/|title=Cowboys Dancehall: Dallas and San Antonio|website=CowboysDancehall.com|access-date=2019-03-26}}</ref> (Dallas and San Antonio), John T. Floore's Country Store<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liveatfloores.com/|title=John T. Floore Country Store|website=John T. Floore Country Store|language=en|access-date=2019-03-26}}</ref>(Helotes), [[Luckenbach, Texas#Country_music|Luckenbach Dance Hall]], and Blue Light Live<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wideopencountry.com/top-country-music-venues-in-texas/|title=The Best Places for Live Country Music in Texas|date=1 March 2017|website=Wideopencountry.com|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> (Lubbock).\n\nIn addition to local and state wide venues hosting live performances, the Texas Regional Radio Report hosts the annual '''Texas Regional Radio Music Awards Show''' where the Texas Red Dirt artist and radio stations are recognized for the outstanding achievements throughout the year. The winners in 25 categories are nominated and voted on by fans, friends and industry professionals and are awarded the night of the show.  The voting membership has grown to over 32,000 voting members in five years and continues to expand every year.  The awards show is open to the public and fans alike who cheer on their favorite artist/entertainers and radio stations.  Information about the show and voting procedures can be found at https://trrma.net/\n\n==Themes==\nLyrical content is the backbone of Texas country. [[Willie Nelson]], a legendary Country Music Outlaw, inspired his friend [[Waylon Jennings]], an outlaw country music legend himself, who is sometimes cited as an inspiration to present day Texas country musicians, to say, \u201cYour melody goes where the words take you\u201d.<ref>Jennings, Waylon and [[Lenny Kaye]].  ''Waylon: An Autobiography.''  New York: Warner Books, 1976.</ref>\n\nThere are 4 different types of themes in Country Music. These include the following categories: \"It's All Over\" (songs with a core theme of loss or regret), It's Not Working Out (songs with a focus on frustration over a relationship), \"Love and Devotion\" (sappy love songs) and \"The Right Way to Live\" (songs with a dominant theme of pride and homespun wisdom).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wideopencountry.com/chart-shows-4-themes-country-songs-50-years/|title=Chart Shows the 4 Themes in Country Music Over 50 Years|last=Smith|first=Lindi|date=2016-05-03|website=Wide Open Country|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\nSongs about traditional dance halls, open roads, family farms and hometown bars, along with other illustrations of Texas landscape, are all found in present-day Texas country artists' catalogs.  The ties of landscape and music seem to serve as remembrance and gratitude, as evident in most songs.  Appreciation for surroundings is not the only limitation for this theme.  The \"average man\" and his struggle with nature do appear as well.  \"The songs definitely incorporate a spirit of the times and constitute a spontaneous and fairly comprehensive record of life\".<ref>Clayton, Lawrence. \"Elements of Realism in the Songs of the Cowboy.\" American Renaissance and American West. Ed. Durer, Christopher S. et al. WY: University of Wyoming, 1982.</ref>\n\nA few things Texas Country Music also have in common are topics that are in their songs such as Religion, Patriotism, Red Neck Lifestyles, and Nostalgia. Religion tends to play a big role in Country Music since its roots are in religion \u2013 being born from Traditional Southern Folk and Gospel music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.westword.com/music/the-ten-biggest-tropes-in-country-music-5694846|title=The ten biggest tropes in country music|last=Rogers|first=Ashley|date=2013-09-05|website=Westword|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref> Patriotism is also big since they love to talk about how much they love their country. For example, \"[[American Soldier (song)|American Soldier]]\" by [[Toby Keith]] is a great example of patriotism being expressed. Texas Country also involves singing about \"redneck lifestyles\" which includes their country living with trucks, tractors, fishing, and guns. Nostalgia is also considered a characteristic that most songs Country songs have.\n\n==History==\n\n===Origination===\n\nCountry Music from Texas has been popular since the spread of the cowboy culture in the late 1800s. Texas helped popularize Country Music through the world and the state\u2019s rich and varied traditions continue to redefine Country Music.<ref>Hartman, Gary. The History of Texas Music. N.p.: Texas A&M University Press, 2008. Print.</ref>\n\nTexas Country's roots lie in the [[Outlaw country]] movement of the 1960s and 1970s.  Texan artists such as [[Waylon Jennings]], [[Willie Nelson]], and [[David Allan Coe]] retreated from the Nashville Country Music scene to [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], [[Luckenbach, Texas|Luckenbach]], [[College station, tx|College Station]] and [[Houston]]. Other artists who were inspired by this movement included performers like [[Guy Clark]], [[Jerry Jeff Walker]], Gary P. Nunn [[Steve Young (musician)|Steve Young]], [[Kris Kristofferson]], [[Joe Ely]], [[Terry Allen (country singer)|Terry Allen]], [[Steve Earle]],  and [[Townes Van Zandt]]. All these stars have rated higher than 43 on the Texas Music Scene charts{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}.\n\nThese artists were followed in turn by the work of singer-songwriters such as [[Pat Green]], [[Robert Earl Keen]], [[Max Stalling]], [[Wade Bowen]] and [[Cory Morrow]].\n\nWhile the genre has roots in Texas, Oklahoma artists such as [[Jason Boland & The Stragglers|Jason Boland]], [[Stoney LaRue]], [[Mike McClure]], and [[Cross Canadian Ragweed]] have had a major influence on Texas Country. For this reason, \"Red Dirt Music\" is becoming a more popular term for the genre to pay homage to its Oklahoma influence. The term was coined in reference to the miles of red dirt that is common throughout the two states.\n\n===1990s===\n[[Robert Earl Keen]]'s ''[[No. 2 Live Dinner]]'', released in 1996, had it all; comedy accompanied with \"a sharp wit, a laid-back cowboy style, and an eye for detail... combined in [his] songs that are as easy on the ears as they are packed with insight\".<ref>Wolff, Kurt.  ''Country Music: The Rough Guide.''  London: Rough Guides Ltd, 2000.</ref>  Keen's home calling came after a short stint in Nashville, where he quickly became uncomfortable.  His 1996 live album release truly showcased the \u201cwide range\u201d of the talented Texas musician and popularized the single \"The Road Goes On Forever\", a song many music fans regard as the paradigm for Texas 'Country anthems'. [[Joe Ely]] and other Texas musicians have recorded cover versions of \u201cThe Road Goes On Forever\u201d.\n<!--\n RECOMMEND IMMEDIATE REMOVAL:\n no reference to verify these claims can be located.\nThe 1998 release of [[Roger Creager]]\u2019s ''Having Fun All Wrong'' had an immediate impact on the Texas scene.  \u201cThe Everclear Song\u201d reached \u201chit single\u201d status when it quickly spread across Texas college towns and has often been called \"The Anthem of Texas Country.\"{{Fact|date=July 2007}}.\n-->\n\n===2000s and the Texas influence in Nashville===\n\n[[Cory Morrow]], a [[Houston]] native, had been on the Texas scene since the mid-90s. With the release of his fourth album ''Outside the Lines'', Morrow found more mainstream success on the Country Music charts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kbec.com/texas-music-facts-tales/|title=Texas Music Facts and Some Tales|last=kbec|date=2017-10-24|website=KBEC 1390|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n[[Pat Green]], also an artist from Texas, began his career as part of the Texas Country scene later went on to widespread commercial success with gold album ''[[Wave on Wave]]'' after switching to a  \"Shania Twain/ Garth Brooks\" Nashville style of Country Music.  The album's title track hit No. 3 on the U.S. ''Billboard's'' Hot Country Songs chart and won a [[Grammy]] nomination for Best Country Song.\n\n[[Kevin Fowler]], a former hair-metal/glam rocker was [[Dangerous Toys]] guitarist from the late 1980s until 1993, followed by his own founding of Thunderfoot, a Southern rock band based out of Austin. Originally from [[Amarillo]], he self-released his country debut album ''One For The Road'' in 1997. This followed with his smash independent follow-up album, ''Beer, Bait, and Ammo''.  He has since found national success, on a major label.\n\nTexas Country's influence continues to be felt in the mainstream music genre with artists such as [[Jack Ingram]], who had already established a name for himself in Texas Country, who won a [[CMT Music Award]] in 2007 and the 2008 [[Academy of Country Music]] award for New Male Vocalist of the Year.  He has also scored top 25 singles on ''Billboard's'' Hot Country Songs chart with songs such as \"[[Love You (Jack Ingram song)|Love You]]\" and his cover of [[Hinder|Hinder's]] \"[[Lips of an Angel]]\".  Another one of his singles, \"[[Wherever You Are (Jack Ingram song)|Wherever You Are]]\", went to number one on the Billboard Chart.\n\nMany independent artists, which is the fastest growing segment of the global recorded music business, <ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/melissamdaniels/2019/07/10/for-independent-musicians-goingyour-own-way-is-finally-starting-to-pay-off/#45980f4f14f2</ref> have gained commercial success through the Texas music scene, such as albums debuting in the Top 5 of Billboard's Top Country Album sales. <ref>https://www.houstonpress.com/music/indie-texas-country-artists-racking-up-major-league-sales-8721118</ref>\n\n==Radio stations==\nTexas Country is unique in that radio stations throughout Texas have embraced the subgenre and regularly mix Texas country into a Country radio format:\n\n===Internet===\n*[[Texas Country Mix (Internet Radio)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.txcountrymix.com/|title=Texas Country Mix (Internet Radio)}}</ref>\n*[[GotRadio Texas Best (Internet Radio)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gotradio.com/|title=GotRadio Texas Best (Internet Radio)}}</ref>\n\n===Terrestrial (AM/FM)===\n*[[KBSO|KBSO 94.7 Corpus Christi, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://947jalapenocountry.com|title=KBSO 94.7 Corpus Christi, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KFLP-FM|KFLP 106.1 Floydada/Plainview/Lubbock, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://1061flipfm.com|title=KFLP 106.1 Floydada/Plainview/Lubbock, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KFWR|KFWR 95.9 Fort Worth, Texas]]\n*[[KFYN-FM|KFYN 104.3 Paris, Texas]]\n*[[KILT-FM|KILT 100.3 HD3 Houston, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thebull.radio.com|title=KILT 100.3 HD3 Houston, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KKBQ|KKBQ 92.9 HD3 Pasadena, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thenew93q.com|title=KKBQ 92.9 HD3 Pasadena, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KKCN|KKCN 103.1 San Angelo, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://103kkcn.com|title=KKCN 103.1 San Angelo, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KNBT|KNBT 92.1 New Braunfels, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.knbt.fm|title=KNBT 92.1 New Braunfels, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KOLI|KOLI 94.9 Wichita Falls, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://949theoutlaw.com|title=KOLI 94.9 Wichita Falls, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KOKE|KOKE 99.3/98.5 Austin, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokefm.com|title=KOKE 99.3/98.5 Austin, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KORA|KORA 98.3 Bryan/College Station, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://983korafm.com|title=KORA 98.3 Bryan/College Station, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KPLX|KPLX 99.5 Dallas/Ft. Worth, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://995thewolf.com|title=KPLX 99.5 Dallas/Ft. Worth, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KRMX|KRMX 92.9 Waco, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shooterfm.com|title=KRMX 92.9 Waco, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KRVA|KRVA 107.1 Campbell, Texas]]\n*[[KTEX|KTEX 106.1 Brenham, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ktex.com|title=KTEX 106.1 Brenham, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KTWL|KTWL 105.3 Brenham, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://texasmix1053.com|title=KTWL 105.3 Brenham, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KWHI|KWHI 101.7 Brenham, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kwhi.com|title=KWHI 101.7 Brenham, Texas}}</ref>\n\n==Syndicated radio programs==\nSeveral [[broadcast syndication|regionally syndicated]] programs feature the format: \n\n*[[CDTex Radio Show|CDTex Radio Show]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cdtex.com|title=CDTex Radio Show}}</ref>\n*[[Official Texas Countdown|Official Texas Countdown]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://texascountdown.com|title=Official Texas Countdown}}</ref>\n*[[Scotty Bennett's Texas Nights|Scotty Bennett's Texas Nights]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokefm.com/texas-nights-2|title=Scotty Bennett's Texas Nights}}</ref>\n\n==Tracking==\nRadio play in Texas music is tracked, recorded, and reported by the Texas Regional Radio Report, which also distributes annual awards for various categories, such as male and female vocalists of the year. <ref>https://www.texasregionalradio.com/</ref>\n\n==Notable artists==\n{{multiple issues|section=yes|\n{{indiscriminate list|section|date=June 2019}}\n{{unsourced section|date=July 2019}}\n}}\nThe following artists are often classified{{whom|date=June 2019}} as members of the Texas country movement:\n{{columns-list|* [[ Aaron Watson ]]\n* [[ Adam Carroll (American musician)|Adam Carroll]]\n* [[ Adam Hood ]]\n* [[ Asleep at the Wheel ]]\n* [[ Bill Pekar ]]\n* [[ Billy Joe Shaver ]]\n* [[ Blue Edmondson ]]\n* [[ Brandon Kinney ]]\n* [[ Brandon Rhyder ]]\n* [[Brian Burns (musician)|Brian Burns]]\n* [[ Brian Keane ]]\n* [[ Broken DuckFeet ]]\n* [[ Bruce Robison ]]\n* [[ Casey Donahew ]]\n* [[ Chad Cooke ]]\n* [[ Charlie Robison ]]\n* [[Chris Knight (musician)| Chris Knight ]]\n* [[ Chuck Hawthorne ]]\n* [[ Clint Martin ]]\n* [[ Cody Canada ]]\n* [[ Cody Jinks ]]\n* [[ Cody Johnson ]]\n* [[ Cooder Graw ]]\n* [[ Corb Lund ]]\n* [[ Cory Morrow ]]\n* [[ Cross Canadian Ragweed ]]\n* [[Dale Watson (singer)| Dale Watson ]]\n* [[ Davin James ]]\n* [[ Delbert McClinton ]]\n* [[ Deryl Dodd ]]\n* [[ Dirty River Boys ]]\n* [[ Django Walker ]]\n* [[ Doug Moreland ]]\n* [[ Dub Miller ]]\n* [[ Dusty Neuman ]]\n* [[ Ed Burleson ]]\n* [[ Eleven Hundred Springs ]]\n* [[ Eli Young Band ]]\n* [[ Flatland Cavalry ]]\n* [[ Floyd Tolston ]]\n* [[ Foster and Lloyd ]]\n* [[ Fred Eaglesmith ]]\n* [[ Gary Floater ]]\n* [[ Gary Kyle ]]\n* [[ Gary P. Nunn ]]\n* [[ George Strait ]]\n* [[ Granger Smith ]]\n* [[ Gurf Morlix ]]\n* [[ Guy Clark ]]\n* [[ Hayes Carll ]]\n* [[ Highspeed Hayride ]]\n* [[ Jack Ingram ]]\n* [[ Jackson Taylor & The Sinners ]]\n* [[ Jake Kellen ]]\n* [[ Jake Penrod ]]\n* [[ James Lann ]]\n* [[ James McMurtry ]]\n* [[ Jamie Richards ]]\n* [[ Jarrod Birmingham ]]\n* [[Jason Allen (musician)|Jason Allen]]\n* [[ Jason Boland & the Stragglers ]]\n* [[ Jason Eady ]]\n* [[Jason James (American musician)|Jason James]]\n* [[ JB and the Moonshine Band ]]\n* [[ Jerry Jeff Walker ]]\n* [[ Jesse Brand ]]\n* [[ Jim Lauderdale ]]\n* [[ Jimmy & David Lee Kaiser ]]\n* [[ Jody Booth ]]\n* [[John Baumann]]\n* [[ John David Kent and the Dumb Angels ]]\n* [[John Slaughter (musician)|John Slaughter]]\n* [[ Johnny Cash ]]\n* [[ Johnny Falstaff ]]\n* [[ Jon Wolfe ]]\n* [[ Josh Abbott Band ]]\n* [[ Josh Ward ]]\n* [[ Junior Brown ]]\n* [[ Kacey Musgraves ]]\n* [[ Kelly Willis ]]\n* [[ Kevin Fowler ]]\n* [[ Kevin Jackson ]]\n* [[ Kinky Friedman ]]\n* [[ Koe Wetzel ]]\n* [[ Kyle Park ]]\n* [[ Kylie Rae Harris ]]\n* [[ Larry Joe Taylor ]]\n* [[ Luke Olson ]]\n* [[ Lyle Lovett ]]\n* [[ Mark David Manders ]]\n* [[ Mark McKinney ]]\n* [[ Mark Sanders ]]\n* [[ Mark Winston Kirk ]]\n* [[ Matt Hillyer ]]\n* [[ Matt Powell ]]\n* [[ Max Stalling ]]\n* [[ McKay Brothers ]]\n* [[ Michael Anthony Rodriguez ]]\n* [[ Micky & the Motorcars ]]\n* [[Midland (band)| Midland ]]\n* [[ Mike and the Moonpies ]]\n* [[ Mike Ethan Messick ]]\n* [[ Mike McClure Band ]]\n* [[Mike Ryan (musician)| Mike Ryan ]]\n* [[ No Justice ]]\n* [[ Old Crow Medicine Show ]]\n* [[ Owen Temple ]]\n* [[ Parker McCollum ]]\n* [[ Pat Green ]]\n* [[ Paul Eason ]]\n* [[Peter Dawson (country musician)|Peter Dawson]]\n* [[ Prophets and Outlaws ]]\n* [[ Randall King ]]\n* [[ Radney Foster ]]\n* [[ Randy Rogers Band ]]\n* [[ Ray Wylie Hubbard ]]\n* [[ Reckless Kelly (band)|Reckless Kelly ]]\n* [[ Ricky Calmbach ]]\n* [[ Rio Grand ]]\n* [[ Robert Earl Keen ]]\n* [[ Rodney Hayden ]]\n* [[ Rodney Parker ]]\n* [[ Roger Creager ]]\n* [[ Rumor Town ]]\n* [[ Rusty Wier ]]\n* [[ Ryan Beaver ]]\n* [[ Ryan Bingham ]]\n* [[ Sam Riggs ]]\n* [[ Shy Blakeman ]]\n* [[ Slaid Cleaves ]]\n* [[ Sonny Burgess ]]\n* [[ Sons of Bill ]]\n* [[ Sour Bridges ]]\n* [[ Steve Earle ]]\n* [[ Steve Griggs Band ]]\n* [[ Steve Helms ]]\n* [[ Steve Ripley ]]\n* [[ Stoney LaRue ]]\n* [[ Sundance Head ]]\n* [[ Sunny Sweeney ]]\n* [[ Tejas Brothers ]]\n* [[Terry Allen (artist)| Terry Allen ]]\n* [[ Texas Tornados ]]\n* [[ The Damn Quails ]]\n* [[ The Derailers ]]\n* [[ The Flatlanders ]]\n* [[ The Geezinslaws ]]\n* [[ The Gourds ]]\n* [[The Great Divide (band)| The Great Divide ]]\n* [[ The Reverend Horton Heat ]]\n* [[ Todd Fritcsh ]]\n* [[ Todd Snider ]]\n* [[ Tommy Alverson ]]\n* [[ Townes Van Zandt ]]\n* [[ Trent Summar ]]\n* [[ Turnpike Troubadours ]]\n* [[ Two Tons of Steel ]]\n* [[ Uncle Lucius ]]\n* [[ Wade Bowen ]]\n* [[ Whiskey Myers ]]\n* [[ William Clark Green ]]\n* [[ Willie Nelson ]]\n* [[ Zack Walther ]]\n* [[ Zane Williams ]]\n* [[ Zona Jones ]]|colwidth=20em}}\n\nMany of these artists maintain a yearly membership with the Texas Country Music Association, a community of touring and recording artists, songwriters, and many other contributors to the Texas music industry.<ref>https://texascountrymusicassociation.org/</ref>\n\n[[Royal Caribbean International]] and Luxx Vacations have partnered with various sponsors to host a Texas Country Music Cruise on the [[Liberty of the Seas]], featuring many Texas music artists such as Cory Morrow, William Clark Green, and Bri Bagwell. <ref>https://www.texascountrymusiccruise.com/index.html</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Abernethy, Francis E. \"Texas Folk and Modern Country Music\". ''Texas Country: The Changing Rural Scene''. Ed. Lich, Glene. College Station, TX: [[Texas A&M University Press]], 1986.\n* Barr, Gregory. \"Randy Rogers Band: Just a Matter of Time\". ''Best in Texas Music Magazine''.\n* Carr, Joe and Allan Munde. ''Prairie Nights to Neon Lights''. Lubbock: [[Texas Tech University Press]], 1995, {{ISBN|9780896723658}}\n* Dawidoff, Nicholas. ''In the Country of Country: People and Places in American Music''. New York: [[Random House]], 1997, {{ISBN|978-0375700828}}\n* Fox, Aaron A. ''Real Country: Music and Language in Working-Class Culture''. Durham, NC: [[Duke University Press]], 2004, {{ISBN| 978-0822333487}}\n* Harrington, Ann Marie. ''Roger Creager - Long Way to Mexico''\n* Jennings, Waylon and [[Lenny Kaye]]. ''Waylon: An Autobiography''. New York: [[Warner Books]], 1976, {{ISBN| 978-1613744697}}\n* Malone, Bill C. \"Growing Up With Texas Country Music.\" ''What's Going On? (In Modern Texas Folklore)''. Ed. Abernethy, Francis E. Austin, TX: [[William D. Wittliff|The Encino Press]], 1976.\n* Middleton, Richard. ''Studying Popular Music''. Philadelphia: [[Open University Press]], 2002., {{ISBN|978-0335152759}}\n* Specht, Joe W. \"Put a Nickel in the Jukebox\". ''The Roots of Texas Music''. Ed. Clayton Lawrence. College Station, TX: [[Texas A&M University Press]], 2003.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Country music}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Texas Country Music}}\n[[Category:Texas country music| ]]\n[[Category:Country music genres]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Original research|date=November 2009}}\n{{Essay-like|date=November 2009}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2019}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox music genre\n|name=Texas country music \n|bgcolor=brown\n|color=white\n|stylistic_origins={{hlist|[[Country music|Country]]|[[Western music (North America)|Western]]|[[outlaw country]]}}\n|cultural_origins=Late 1960s, [[Texas]], United States\n|instruments={{hlist|[[Acoustic guitar]]|[[electric guitar]]|[[steel guitar]]|[[bass guitar]]|[[percussion]]|[[banjo]]|[[mandolin]]|[[Dobro]]|[[fiddle]]|[[piano]]|[[harmonica]]}}\n|popularity=[[Texas]]\n|derivatives={{hlist|[[Neotraditional country]]\n|[[progressive country]]\n|[[Red Dirt (music)|Red Dirt]]}}}}\n\n'''Texas Country Music''' (more popularly known just as '''Texas Country''' or '''Texas Music''') is a rapidly growing subgenre of [[country music]] from [[Texas]]. Texas country is a unique style of [[Western music (North America)|Western music]] and is often associated with other distinct neighboring styles,<ref name=\"Galit Simmons 2005 p. 68\">{{cite book | last=Galit | first=E.L. | last2=Simmons | first2=V. | title=Exploring Texas History: Weekend Adventures | publisher=Taylor Trade Publishing | year=2005 | isbn=978-1-58979-202-9 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=poDYKu4UHjAC&pg=PA68 | language=nl | access-date=2020-04-12 | page=68}}</ref> including [[Red Dirt (music)|Red Dirt]] from [[Oklahoma]],<ref name=\"Semer p. 3\">{{cite book | last=Semer | first=A. | title=T is For Texas | isbn=978-1-387-78328-1 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zIVaDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA3 | access-date=2020-04-12 | page=3}}</ref> the [[New Mexico music]] of [[New Mexico]],<ref name=\"Billboard p. 49\">{{cite book | title=Billboard | publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc. | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RAkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT49 | language=de | access-date=2020-04-12 | page=49}}</ref> and [[Tejano music|Tejano]] in [[West Texas]].<ref name=\"Jasinski Monahan 2012 p. 553\">{{cite book | last=Jasinski | first=L.E. | last2=Monahan | first2=C. | title=Handbook of Texas Music | publisher=Texas State Historical Assn | year=2012 | isbn=978-0-87611-297-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CE8xiT3pV6QC&pg=PT553 | access-date=2020-04-12 | page=553}}</ref> All of which have influenced one another over the years, and are popular throughout Texas, the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]], the  [[Southwestern United States|Southwest]], and other parts of the [[Western United States]]. Texas Country is known for fusing [[Neotraditional country|neotraditional country]] with the outspoken, care-free views of [[outlaw country]]. Texas Country blends these sub-genres with a [[common people|\"common working man\"]] theme and witty undertones, these often combine with a stripped down music sound.\n\nNeither the location of birth nor the location of upbringing seems to calculate in the definition of a Texas Country artist, as long as the origin is not in the corporate Nashville scene as the genre tends to be anti-Nashville. The genre differentiates from Nashville country with its rejection of pop influences that is found in Nashville Country recently, but does not necessarily mean the artist/group is Texas based.  For example, [[Chris Knight (musician)|Chris Knight]] is considered by some to be a Texas Country musician, despite his [[Kentucky]] ties. [[Adam Hood]], an [[Alabama]] native, also has had success in the genre. Even international musicians, such as [[Alberta, Canada]] native [[Corb Lund]], have been successful in the Texas Country scene. This just shows how many musicians all over the world have adopted the Texas sound.\n\n==Instrumentation==\n{{unsourced section|date=July 2019}}\nThe [[Steel-string guitar|acoustic guitar]] is essential in Texas Country Music. However, the use of [[electric guitar]]s, [[steel guitar]]s or [[pedal steel guitar]]s in the genre is not uncommon. [[bass guitar|Bass]] and [[percussion]] are used in live performances. The sounds of [[piano]], [[baritone guitar]], [[banjo]], [[accordion]], [[fiddle]] or [[harmonica]] on studio recordings are the norm for the genre.\n\n==Vocals==\nThe line of delineation for vocals is unclear. Traditionally, the Texas Country scene has been a male dominated genre, however many women have had chart success in recent years. The Texas \"anthem\" is a common song type, referencing and sometimes embellishing on the different positive characteristics of the state. Many of these types of songs have been popular on the Texas Music Charts.<ref>[http://www.countryradioclassics.com/index.php/2007/09/21/texas-national-anthem-voting/ TX National Anthem voting ] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080703153140/http://www.countryradioclassics.com/index.php/2007/09/21/texas-national-anthem-voting |date=2008-07-03 }} (sponsored by Lone-Star Beer company)</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\nThe live performance is at the very root of the Texas Country scene.  Enthusiasm is the best descriptor for both band and crowd at a live Texas Country performance. \"It is not an uncommon sight to see clubs all over Texas packed to the rafters; girls and boys in cowboy hats and [[Wrangler Jeans|Wranglers]] [[Country-western two-step|two-step]]ping next to the mosh pit, where [[frat boy|college boys or \"Man Fans\"]] in khakis and college girls pressed up against the stage\".<ref>Lone Star Music. Kevin Fowler Biography. [http://www.lonestarmusic.com/biography.asp?id=86 November 9, 2006] LoneStar Music.</ref> An important factor Texas Country's success is in the frequency of live performances. It is not uncommon for a Texas Country band to tour 200+ dates a year, all, or nearly all, in the State of Texas{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}. This allows the fan to attend a band's show more often, thus interacting with the music on a more personal level.\nPopular venues include, [[Gruene Hall]] (Gruene), [[Billy Bob's]] (Ft. Worth), [http://www.cowboysdancehall.com/dallas/ Cowboys Red River]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cowboysdancehall.com/|title=Cowboys Dancehall: Dallas and San Antonio|website=CowboysDancehall.com|access-date=2019-03-26}}</ref> (Dallas and San Antonio), John T. Floore's Country Store<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liveatfloores.com/|title=John T. Floore Country Store|website=John T. Floore Country Store|language=en|access-date=2019-03-26}}</ref>(Helotes), [[Luckenbach, Texas#Country_music|Luckenbach Dance Hall]], and Blue Light Live<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wideopencountry.com/top-country-music-venues-in-texas/|title=The Best Places for Live Country Music in Texas|date=1 March 2017|website=Wideopencountry.com|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> (Lubbock).\n\nIn addition to local and state wide venues hosting live performances, the Texas Regional Radio Report hosts the annual '''Texas Regional Radio Music Awards Show''' where the Texas Red Dirt artist and radio stations are recognized for the outstanding achievements throughout the year. The winners in 25 categories are nominated and voted on by fans, friends and industry professionals and are awarded the night of the show.  The voting membership has grown to over 32,000 voting members in five years and continues to expand every year.  The awards show is open to the public and fans alike who cheer on their favorite artist/entertainers and radio stations.  Information about the show and voting procedures can be found at https://trrma.net/\n\n==Themes==\nLyrical content is the backbone of Texas country. [[Willie Nelson]], a legendary Country Music Outlaw, inspired his friend [[Waylon Jennings]], an outlaw country music legend himself, who is sometimes cited as an inspiration to present day Texas country musicians, to say, \u201cYour melody goes where the words take you\u201d.<ref>Jennings, Waylon and [[Lenny Kaye]].  ''Waylon: An Autobiography.''  New York: Warner Books, 1976.</ref>\n\nThere are 4 different types of themes in Country Music. These include the following categories: \"It's All Over\" (songs with a core theme of loss or regret), It's Not Working Out (songs with a focus on frustration over a relationship), \"Love and Devotion\" (sappy love songs) and \"The Right Way to Live\" (songs with a dominant theme of pride and homespun wisdom).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wideopencountry.com/chart-shows-4-themes-country-songs-50-years/|title=Chart Shows the 4 Themes in Country Music Over 50 Years|last=Smith|first=Lindi|date=2016-05-03|website=Wide Open Country|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\nSongs about traditional dance halls, open roads, family farms and hometown bars, along with other illustrations of Texas landscape, are all found in present-day Texas country artists' catalogs.  The ties of landscape and music seem to serve as remembrance and gratitude, as evident in most songs.  Appreciation for surroundings is not the only limitation for this theme.  The \"average man\" and his struggle with nature do appear as well.  \"The songs definitely incorporate a spirit of the times and constitute a spontaneous and fairly comprehensive record of life\".<ref>Clayton, Lawrence. \"Elements of Realism in the Songs of the Cowboy.\" American Renaissance and American West. Ed. Durer, Christopher S. et al. WY: University of Wyoming, 1982.</ref>\n\nA few things Texas Country Music also have in common are topics that are in their songs such as Religion, Patriotism, Red Neck Lifestyles, and Nostalgia. Religion tends to play a big role in Country Music since its roots are in religion \u2013 being born from Traditional Southern Folk and Gospel music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.westword.com/music/the-ten-biggest-tropes-in-country-music-5694846|title=The ten biggest tropes in country music|last=Rogers|first=Ashley|date=2013-09-05|website=Westword|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref> Patriotism is also big since they love to talk about how much they love their country. For example, \"[[American Soldier (song)|American Soldier]]\" by [[Toby Keith]] is a great example of patriotism being expressed. Texas Country also involves singing about \"redneck lifestyles\" which includes their country living with trucks, tractors, fishing, and guns. Nostalgia is also considered a characteristic that most songs Country songs have.\n\n==History==\n\n===Origination===\n\nCountry Music from Texas has been popular since the spread of the cowboy culture in the late 1800s. Texas helped popularize Country Music through the world and the state\u2019s rich and varied traditions continue to redefine Country Music.<ref>Hartman, Gary. The History of Texas Music. N.p.: Texas A&M University Press, 2008. Print.</ref>\n\nTexas Country's roots lie in the [[Outlaw country]] movement of the 1960s and 1970s.  Texan artists such as [[Waylon Jennings]], [[Willie Nelson]], and [[David Allan Coe]] retreated from the Nashville Country Music scene to [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], [[Luckenbach, Texas|Luckenbach]], [[College station, tx|College Station]] and [[Houston]]. Other artists who were inspired by this movement included performers like [[Guy Clark]], [[Jerry Jeff Walker]], Gary P. Nunn [[Steve Young (musician)|Steve Young]], [[Kris Kristofferson]], [[Joe Ely]], [[Terry Allen (country singer)|Terry Allen]], [[Steve Earle]],  and [[Townes Van Zandt]]. All these stars have rated higher than 43 on the Texas Music Scene charts{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}.\n\nThese artists were followed in turn by the work of singer-songwriters such as [[Pat Green]], [[Robert Earl Keen]], [[Max Stalling]], [[Wade Bowen]] and [[Cory Morrow]].\n\nWhile the genre has roots in Texas, Oklahoma artists such as [[Jason Boland & The Stragglers|Jason Boland]], [[Stoney LaRue]], [[Mike McClure]], and [[Cross Canadian Ragweed]] have had a major influence on Texas Country. For this reason, \"Red Dirt Music\" is becoming a more popular term for the genre to pay homage to its Oklahoma influence. The term was coined in reference to the miles of red dirt that is common throughout the two states.\n\n===1990s===\n[[Robert Earl Keen]]'s ''[[No. 2 Live Dinner]]'', released in 1996, had it all; comedy accompanied with \"a sharp wit, a laid-back cowboy style, and an eye for detail... combined in [his] songs that are as easy on the ears as they are packed with insight\".<ref>Wolff, Kurt.  ''Country Music: The Rough Guide.''  London: Rough Guides Ltd, 2000.</ref>  Keen's home calling came after a short stint in Nashville, where he quickly became uncomfortable.  His 1996 live album release truly showcased the \u201cwide range\u201d of the talented Texas musician and popularized the single \"The Road Goes On Forever\", a song many music fans regard as the paradigm for Texas 'Country anthems'. [[Joe Ely]] and other Texas musicians have recorded cover versions of \u201cThe Road Goes On Forever\u201d.\n<!--\n RECOMMEND IMMEDIATE REMOVAL:\n no reference to verify these claims can be located.\nThe 1998 release of [[Roger Creager]]\u2019s ''Having Fun All Wrong'' had an immediate impact on the Texas scene.  \u201cThe Everclear Song\u201d reached \u201chit single\u201d status when it quickly spread across Texas college towns and has often been called \"The Anthem of Texas Country.\"{{Fact|date=July 2007}}.\n-->\n\n===2000s and the Texas influence in Nashville===\n\n[[Cory Morrow]], a [[Houston]] native, had been on the Texas scene since the mid-90s. With the release of his fourth album ''Outside the Lines'', Morrow found more mainstream success on the Country Music charts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kbec.com/texas-music-facts-tales/|title=Texas Music Facts and Some Tales|last=kbec|date=2017-10-24|website=KBEC 1390|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n[[Pat Green]], also an artist from Texas, began his career as part of the Texas Country scene later went on to widespread commercial success with gold album ''[[Wave on Wave]]'' after switching to a  \"Shania Twain/ Garth Brooks\" Nashville style of Country Music.  The album's title track hit No. 3 on the U.S. ''Billboard's'' Hot Country Songs chart and won a [[Grammy]] nomination for Best Country Song.\n\n[[Kevin Fowler]], a former hair-metal/glam rocker was [[Dangerous Toys]] guitarist from the late 1980s until 1993, followed by his own founding of Thunderfoot, a Southern rock band based out of Austin. Originally from [[Amarillo]], he self-released his country debut album ''One For The Road'' in 1997. This followed with his smash independent follow-up album, ''Beer, Bait, and Ammo''.  He has since found national success, on a major label.\n\nTexas Country's influence continues to be felt in the mainstream music genre with artists such as [[Jack Ingram]], who had already established a name for himself in Texas Country, who won a [[CMT Music Award]] in 2007 and the 2008 [[Academy of Country Music]] award for New Male Vocalist of the Year.  He has also scored top 25 singles on ''Billboard's'' Hot Country Songs chart with songs such as \"[[Love You (Jack Ingram song)|Love You]]\" and his cover of [[Hinder|Hinder's]] \"[[Lips of an Angel]]\".  Another one of his singles, \"[[Wherever You Are (Jack Ingram song)|Wherever You Are]]\", went to number one on the Billboard Chart.\n\nMany independent artists, which is the fastest growing segment of the global recorded music business, <ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/melissamdaniels/2019/07/10/for-independent-musicians-goingyour-own-way-is-finally-starting-to-pay-off/#45980f4f14f2</ref> have gained commercial success through the Texas music scene, such as albums debuting in the Top 5 of Billboard's Top Country Album sales. <ref>https://www.houstonpress.com/music/indie-texas-country-artists-racking-up-major-league-sales-8721118</ref>\n\n==Radio stations==\nTexas Country is unique in that radio stations throughout Texas have embraced the subgenre and regularly mix Texas country into a Country radio format:\n\n===Internet===\n*[[Texas Country Mix (Internet Radio)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.txcountrymix.com/|title=Texas Country Mix (Internet Radio)}}</ref>\n*[[GotRadio Texas Best (Internet Radio)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gotradio.com/|title=GotRadio Texas Best (Internet Radio)}}</ref>\n\n===Terrestrial (AM/FM)===\n*[[KBSO|KBSO 94.7 Corpus Christi, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://947jalapenocountry.com|title=KBSO 94.7 Corpus Christi, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KFLP-FM|KFLP 106.1 Floydada/Plainview/Lubbock, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://1061flipfm.com|title=KFLP 106.1 Floydada/Plainview/Lubbock, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KFWR|KFWR 95.9 Fort Worth, Texas]]\n*[[KFYN-FM|KFYN 104.3 Paris, Texas]]\n*[[KILT|KILT 100.3 HD3 Houston, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thebull.radio.com|title=KILT 100.3 HD3 Houston, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KKBQ|KKBQ 92.9 HD3 Pasadena, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thenew93q.com|title=KKBQ 92.9 HD3 Pasadena, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KKCN|KKCN 103.1 San Angelo, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://103kkcn.com|title=KKCN 103.1 San Angelo, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KNBT|KNBT 92.1 New Braunfels, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.knbt.fm|title=KNBT 92.1 New Braunfels, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KOLI|KOLI 94.9 Wichita Falls, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://949theoutlaw.com|title=KOLI 94.9 Wichita Falls, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KOKE|KOKE 99.3/98.5 Austin, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokefm.com|title=KOKE 99.3/98.5 Austin, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KORA|KORA 98.3 Bryan/College Station, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://983korafm.com|title=KORA 98.3 Bryan/College Station, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KPLX|KPLX 99.5 Dallas/Ft. Worth, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://995thewolf.com|title=KPLX 99.5 Dallas/Ft. Worth, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KRMX|KRMX 92.9 Waco, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shooterfm.com|title=KRMX 92.9 Waco, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KRVA|KRVA 107.1 Campbell, Texas]]\n*[[KTEX|KTEX 106.1 Brenham, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ktex.com|title=KTEX 106.1 Brenham, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KTWL|KTWL 105.3 Brenham, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://texasmix1053.com|title=KTWL 105.3 Brenham, Texas}}</ref>\n*[[KWHI|KWHI 101.7 Brenham, Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kwhi.com|title=KWHI 101.7 Brenham, Texas}}</ref>\n\n==Syndicated radio programs==\nSeveral [[broadcast syndication|regionally syndicated]] programs feature the format: \n\n*[[CDTex Radio Show|CDTex Radio Show]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cdtex.com|title=CDTex Radio Show}}</ref>\n*[[Official Texas Countdown|Official Texas Countdown]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://texascountdown.com|title=Official Texas Countdown}}</ref>\n*[[Scotty Bennett's Texas Nights|Scotty Bennett's Texas Nights]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kokefm.com/texas-nights-2|title=Scotty Bennett's Texas Nights}}</ref>\n\n==Tracking==\nRadio play in Texas music is tracked, recorded, and reported by the Texas Regional Radio Report, which also distributes annual awards for various categories, such as male and female vocalists of the year. <ref>https://www.texasregionalradio.com/</ref>\n\n==Notable artists==\n{{multiple issues|section=yes|\n{{indiscriminate list|section|date=June 2019}}\n{{unsourced section|date=July 2019}}\n}}\nThe following artists are often classified{{whom|date=June 2019}} as members of the Texas country movement:\n{{columns-list|* [[ Aaron Watson ]]\n* [[ Adam Carroll (American musician)|Adam Carroll]]\n* [[ Adam Hood ]]\n* [[ Asleep at the Wheel ]]\n* [[ Bill Pekar ]]\n* [[ Billy Joe Shaver ]]\n* [[ Blue Edmondson ]]\n* [[ Brandon Kinney ]]\n* [[ Brandon Rhyder ]]\n* [[Brian Burns (musician)|Brian Burns]]\n* [[ Brian Keane ]]\n* [[ Broken DuckFeet ]]\n* [[ Bruce Robison ]]\n* [[ Casey Donahew ]]\n* [[ Chad Cooke ]]\n* [[ Charlie Robison ]]\n* [[Chris Knight (musician)| Chris Knight ]]\n* [[ Chuck Hawthorne ]]\n* [[ Clint Martin ]]\n* [[ Cody Canada ]]\n* [[ Cody Jinks ]]\n* [[ Cody Johnson ]]\n* [[ Cooder Graw ]]\n* [[ Corb Lund ]]\n* [[ Cory Morrow ]]\n* [[ Cross Canadian Ragweed ]]\n* [[Dale Watson (singer)| Dale Watson ]]\n* [[ Davin James ]]\n* [[ Delbert McClinton ]]\n* [[ Deryl Dodd ]]\n* [[ Dirty River Boys ]]\n* [[ Django Walker ]]\n* [[ Doug Moreland ]]\n* [[ Dub Miller ]]\n* [[ Dusty Neuman ]]\n* [[ Ed Burleson ]]\n* [[ Eleven Hundred Springs ]]\n* [[ Eli Young Band ]]\n* [[ Flatland Cavalry ]]\n* [[ Floyd Tolston ]]\n* [[ Foster and Lloyd ]]\n* [[ Fred Eaglesmith ]]\n* [[ Gary Floater ]]\n* [[ Gary Kyle ]]\n* [[ Gary P. Nunn ]]\n* [[ George Strait ]]\n* [[ Granger Smith ]]\n* [[ Gurf Morlix ]]\n* [[ Guy Clark ]]\n* [[ Hayes Carll ]]\n* [[ Highspeed Hayride ]]\n* [[ Jack Ingram ]]\n* [[ Jackson Taylor & The Sinners ]]\n* [[ Jake Kellen ]]\n* [[ Jake Penrod ]]\n* [[ James Lann ]]\n* [[ James McMurtry ]]\n* [[ Jamie Richards ]]\n* [[ Jarrod Birmingham ]]\n* [[Jason Allen (musician)|Jason Allen]]\n* [[ Jason Boland & the Stragglers ]]\n* [[ Jason Eady ]]\n* [[Jason James (American musician)|Jason James]]\n* [[ JB and the Moonshine Band ]]\n* [[ Jerry Jeff Walker ]]\n* [[ Jesse Brand ]]\n* [[ Jim Lauderdale ]]\n* [[ Jimmy & David Lee Kaiser ]]\n* [[ Jody Booth ]]\n* [[John Baumann]]\n* [[ John David Kent and the Dumb Angels ]]\n* [[John Slaughter (musician)|John Slaughter]]\n* [[ Johnny Cash ]]\n* [[ Johnny Falstaff ]]\n* [[ Jon Wolfe ]]\n* [[ Josh Abbott Band ]]\n* [[ Josh Ward ]]\n* [[ Junior Brown ]]\n* [[ Kacey Musgraves ]]\n* [[ Kelly Willis ]]\n* [[ Kevin Fowler ]]\n* [[ Kevin Jackson ]]\n* [[ Kinky Friedman ]]\n* [[ Koe Wetzel ]]\n* [[ Kyle Park ]]\n* [[ Kylie Rae Harris ]]\n* [[ Larry Joe Taylor ]]\n* [[ Luke Olson ]]\n* [[ Lyle Lovett ]]\n* [[ Mark David Manders ]]\n* [[ Mark McKinney ]]\n* [[ Mark Sanders ]]\n* [[ Mark Winston Kirk ]]\n* [[ Matt Hillyer ]]\n* [[ Matt Powell ]]\n* [[ Max Stalling ]]\n* [[ McKay Brothers ]]\n* [[ Michael Anthony Rodriguez ]]\n* [[ Micky & the Motorcars ]]\n* [[Midland (band)| Midland ]]\n* [[ Mike and the Moonpies ]]\n* [[ Mike Ethan Messick ]]\n* [[ Mike McClure Band ]]\n* [[Mike Ryan (musician)| Mike Ryan ]]\n* [[ No Justice ]]\n* [[ Old Crow Medicine Show ]]\n* [[ Owen Temple ]]\n* [[ Parker McCollum ]]\n* [[ Pat Green ]]\n* [[ Paul Eason ]]\n* [[Peter Dawson (country musician)|Peter Dawson]]\n* [[ Prophets and Outlaws ]]\n* [[ Randall King ]]\n* [[ Radney Foster ]]\n* [[ Randy Rogers Band ]]\n* [[ Ray Wylie Hubbard ]]\n* [[ Reckless Kelly (band)|Reckless Kelly ]]\n* [[ Ricky Calmbach ]]\n* [[ Rio Grand ]]\n* [[ Robert Earl Keen ]]\n* [[ Rodney Hayden ]]\n* [[ Rodney Parker ]]\n* [[ Roger Creager ]]\n* [[ Rumor Town ]]\n* [[ Rusty Wier ]]\n* [[ Ryan Beaver ]]\n* [[ Ryan Bingham ]]\n* [[ Sam Riggs ]]\n* [[ Shy Blakeman ]]\n* [[ Slaid Cleaves ]]\n* [[ Sonny Burgess ]]\n* [[ Sons of Bill ]]\n* [[ Sour Bridges ]]\n* [[ Steve Earle ]]\n* [[ Steve Griggs Band ]]\n* [[ Steve Helms ]]\n* [[ Steve Ripley ]]\n* [[ Stoney LaRue ]]\n* [[ Sundance Head ]]\n* [[ Sunny Sweeney ]]\n* [[ Tejas Brothers ]]\n* [[Terry Allen (artist)| Terry Allen ]]\n* [[ Texas Tornados ]]\n* [[ The Damn Quails ]]\n* [[ The Derailers ]]\n* [[ The Flatlanders ]]\n* [[ The Geezinslaws ]]\n* [[ The Gourds ]]\n* [[The Great Divide (band)| The Great Divide ]]\n* [[ The Reverend Horton Heat ]]\n* [[ Todd Fritcsh ]]\n* [[ Todd Snider ]]\n* [[ Tommy Alverson ]]\n* [[ Townes Van Zandt ]]\n* [[ Trent Summar ]]\n* [[ Turnpike Troubadours ]]\n* [[ Two Tons of Steel ]]\n* [[ Uncle Lucius ]]\n* [[ Wade Bowen ]]\n* [[ Whiskey Myers ]]\n* [[ William Clark Green ]]\n* [[ Willie Nelson ]]\n* [[ Zack Walther ]]\n* [[ Zane Williams ]]\n* [[ Zona Jones ]]|colwidth=20em}}\n\nMany of these artists maintain a yearly membership with the Texas Country Music Association, a community of touring and recording artists, songwriters, and many other contributors to the Texas music industry.<ref>https://texascountrymusicassociation.org/</ref>\n\n[[Royal Caribbean International]] and Luxx Vacations have partnered with various sponsors to host a Texas Country Music Cruise on the [[Liberty of the Seas]], featuring many Texas music artists such as Cory Morrow, William Clark Green, and Bri Bagwell. <ref>https://www.texascountrymusiccruise.com/index.html</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Abernethy, Francis E. \"Texas Folk and Modern Country Music\". ''Texas Country: The Changing Rural Scene''. Ed. Lich, Glene. College Station, TX: [[Texas A&M University Press]], 1986.\n* Barr, Gregory. \"Randy Rogers Band: Just a Matter of Time\". ''Best in Texas Music Magazine''.\n* Carr, Joe and Allan Munde. ''Prairie Nights to Neon Lights''. Lubbock: [[Texas Tech University Press]], 1995, {{ISBN|9780896723658}}\n* Dawidoff, Nicholas. ''In the Country of Country: People and Places in American Music''. New York: [[Random House]], 1997, {{ISBN|978-0375700828}}\n* Fox, Aaron A. ''Real Country: Music and Language in Working-Class Culture''. Durham, NC: [[Duke University Press]], 2004, {{ISBN| 978-0822333487}}\n* Harrington, Ann Marie. ''Roger Creager - Long Way to Mexico''\n* Jennings, Waylon and [[Lenny Kaye]]. ''Waylon: An Autobiography''. New York: [[Warner Books]], 1976, {{ISBN| 978-1613744697}}\n* Malone, Bill C. \"Growing Up With Texas Country Music.\" ''What's Going On? (In Modern Texas Folklore)''. Ed. Abernethy, Francis E. Austin, TX: [[William D. Wittliff|The Encino Press]], 1976.\n* Middleton, Richard. ''Studying Popular Music''. Philadelphia: [[Open University Press]], 2002., {{ISBN|978-0335152759}}\n* Specht, Joe W. \"Put a Nickel in the Jukebox\". ''The Roots of Texas Music''. Ed. Clayton Lawrence. College Station, TX: [[Texas A&M University Press]], 2003.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Country music}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Texas Country Music}}\n[[Category:Texas country music| ]]\n[[Category:Country music genres]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toKILT(link changed toKILT-FM) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Texas_country_music"}
{"title_page": "Vlado Georgiev", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2010}}\n{{update|date=April 2010}}\n{{advert|date=April 2010}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| background        = solo_singer\n| name              = Vlado Georgiev\n| image             = Vlado Georgijev.jpg\n| caption           = Georgijev in 2006\n| birth_name        =  \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1976|6|6}} \n|birth_place        = [[Dubrovnik]], [[Socialist Republic of Croatia|SR Croatia]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]]\n| origin            = [[Herceg Novi]], Montenegro\n| genre             = {{hlist|Pop|[[Pop-rock|rock]]}}\n| occupation        = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|producer|television judge}}\n| instrument        = {{hlist|Vocals|piano}}\n| years_active      = 1996\u2013present\n| label             = {{hlist|Goraton|Barba}}\n| associated_acts   = \n| website           = \n}}\n'''Vladimir \"Vlado\" Georgiev''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u043e \u0413\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0435\u0432}}, {{IPA-sh|\u028bl\u01ce\u02d0do \u0261eor\u0261\u01d0je\u028b|sr}}, born 6 June 1976) is a Serbian singer-songwriter and producer. Georgiev remains one of the most prominent musicians in the Balkans.\n\nGeorgiev served as a judge on television series ''[[Prvi glas Srbije]]'' in 2011 and 2012, and ''[[Tvoje lice zvu\u010di poznato (Serbian season 3)|Tvoje lice zvu\u010di poznato]]'' in 2016.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Family and personal life===\nGeorgiev was born in [[Dubrovnik]] to Dragoljub,<ref name=Puls1>http://www.pulsonline.rs/lifestyle/na-kafi-kod/49/vlado-georgiev-zivim-sam-ali-o-meni-brine-seka</ref> (a [[Bulgarians in Serbia|Bulgarian]] from [[Dimitrovgrad, Serbia|Dimitrovgrad]], Serbia) and Borka<ref name=Puls1/> (a [[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Serb]] from [[Sarajevo]], Bosnia.<ref name=Kurir1>[http://www.kurir-info.rs/stars/vlado-georgiev-odbio-pasos-crne-gore-50976.php Vlado Georgiev odbio paso\u0161 Crne Gore!] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100922044707/http://www.kurir-info.rs/stars/vlado-georgiev-odbio-pasos-crne-gore-50976.php|date=22 September 2010}}, ''Kurir'', 21 September 2010,</ref>) He has an older brother, Sa\u0161a.<ref name=Puls1/>\n\nShortly after his birth, his family moved to [[Herceg Novi]] in Montenegro, where he was raised and lived until age 16,<ref name=Kurir1/> after which he and his brother moved to [[Belgrade]].<ref name=Puls1/> He rides [[motorcycles]],<ref name=Puls1/> and has traveled around Europe on his [[Harley-Davidson]].<ref name=Puls1/>\n\n===Career===\nGeorgiev has recorded three [[music album|studio album]]s to date: ''Navika'' (''Habit'') in 2001, ''\u017dena bez imena'' (''Woman without a name'') in 2003, and ''Daljina'' (''Distance'') in 2013. In 2005, he released a hit single, \"[[Nisam ljubomoran]]\" (\"I'm not jealous\"). After a two-year break he released a single, \"Do svitanja\" (\"Till Dawn\"), along with a ballad, \"Ti i ja\" (\"You and I\"). In 2009, he released two singles, ''Hej ti'' (''Hey You''), which became a huge success, along with a ballad, \"Bez tebe\" (\"Without You\").\n\nHe played harmonica, then he started playing piano, synthesizers and other keyboards. He started writing songs for himself and for the other popular stars in [[ex-Yugoslavia]]. He was also a producer for the [[Montenegro|Montenegrin]] [[hip hop]] band [[Monteniggers]], and is still a friend with their only living member, [[Niggor]]. Georgiev and Niggor recorded the song \"Tropski bar\" together. He has his own record label, ''Barba Music'' and VG-Art studio production company, ''Studio Barba'', in Belgrade. He worked as coach in the two editions of the Serbian version of the talent-show ''The Voice'' (''Prvi glas Srbije'') in 2011\u201312.\n\nHis concerts are always spectacular especially the ones he has been organizing every year in his hometown, Herceg Novi, on Kanli Kula fortress.\n\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n* ''Navika'' (''Habit''), 2001.\n* ''\u017dena bez imena'' (''Woman Without a Name''), 2003.\n* ''Daljina'' (''Distance''), 2013.\n\n===Singles===\n* ''[[Nisam ljubomoran]]'' (''I'm Not Jealous''), 2005.\n* ''Do svitanja'' (''Till Dawn''), 2007.\n* ''Hej ti'' (''Hey You''), 2009.\n* ''Tebe \u017eedan'' (''Thirsty Of You''), 2017.\n* ''Znam te najbolje'' (''I Know You The Best''), 2018.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Music of Serbia]]\n* [[List of people from Serbia#Music|List of singers from Serbia]]\n* [[Serbian pop]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.vladogeorgiev.com}}\n* [http://www.discogs.com/artist/Vlado+Georgiev Vlado Georgiev discography] at [[Discogs]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{succession box\n| before= [[Zorana Pavi\u0107]]\n| title=[[Sun\u010dane Skale]] winner\n| years=1998\n| after=[[Tifa (musician)|Tifa]] & [[Makadam]]\n}}\n{{s-new}}\n{{s-ttl|title= Serbian Oscar Of Popularity<br>''The Male Pop Singer of the Year''\n|years=2009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sergej \u0106etkovi\u0107]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Music of Southeastern Europe (the Balkans)}}\n{{Tvoje lice zvu\u010di poznato}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Georgiev, Vlado}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Serbian pop singers]]\n[[Category:Serbian male singers]]\n[[Category:People from Dubrovnik]]\n[[Category:People from Herceg Novi]]\n[[Category:Serbs of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Serbs of Montenegro]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2010}}\n{{update|date=April 2010}}\n{{advert|date=April 2010}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| background        = solo_singer\n| name              = Vlado Georgiev\n| image             = Vlado Georgijev.jpg\n| caption           = Georgijev in 2006\n| birth_name        =  \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1976|6|6}} \n|birth_place        = [[Dubrovnik]], [[Socialist Republic of Croatia|SR Croatia]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]]\n| origin            = [[Herceg Novi]], Montenegro\n| genre             = {{hlist|Pop|[[Pop-rock|rock]]}}\n| occupation        = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|producer|television judge}}\n| instrument        = {{hlist|Vocals|piano}}\n| years_active      = 1996\u2013present\n| label             = {{hlist|Goraton|Barba}}\n| associated_acts   = \n| website           = \n}}\n'''Vladimir \"Vlado\" Georgiev''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u043e \u0413\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0435\u0432}}, {{IPA-sh|\u028bl\u01ce\u02d0do \u0261eor\u0261\u01d0je\u028b|sr}}, born 6 June 1976) is a Serbian singer-songwriter and producer. Georgiev remains one of the most prominent musicians in the Balkans.\n\nGeorgiev served as a judge on television series ''[[Prvi glas Srbije]]'' in 2011 and 2012, and ''[[Tvoje lice zvu\u010di poznato (Serbian season 3)|Tvoje lice zvu\u010di poznato]]'' in 2016.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Family and personal life===\nGeorgiev was born in [[Dubrovnik]] to Dragoljub,<ref name=Puls1>http://www.pulsonline.rs/lifestyle/na-kafi-kod/49/vlado-georgiev-zivim-sam-ali-o-meni-brine-seka</ref> (a [[Bulgarians in Serbia|Bulgarian]] from [[Dimitrovgrad, Serbia|Dimitrovgrad]], Serbia) and Borka<ref name=Puls1/> (a [[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Serb]] from [[Sarajevo]], Bosnia.<ref name=Kurir1>[http://www.kurir-info.rs/stars/vlado-georgiev-odbio-pasos-crne-gore-50976.php Vlado Georgiev odbio paso\u0161 Crne Gore!] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100922044707/http://www.kurir-info.rs/stars/vlado-georgiev-odbio-pasos-crne-gore-50976.php|date=22 September 2010}}, ''Kurir'', 21 September 2010,</ref>) He has an older brother, Sa\u0161a.<ref name=Puls1/>\n\nShortly after his birth, his family moved to [[Herceg Novi]] in Montenegro, where he was raised and lived until age 16,<ref name=Kurir1/> after which he and his brother moved to [[Belgrade]].<ref name=Puls1/> He rides [[motorcycles]],<ref name=Puls1/> and has traveled around Europe on his [[Harley-Davidson]].<ref name=Puls1/>\n\n===Career===\nGeorgiev has recorded three [[music album|studio album]]s to date: ''Navika'' (''Habit'') in 2001, ''\u017dena bez imena'' (''Woman without a name'') in 2003, and ''Daljina'' (''Distance'') in 2013. In 2005, he released a hit single, \"[[Nisam ljubomoran]]\" (\"I'm not jealous\"). After a two-year break he released a single, \"Do svitanja\" (\"Till Dawn\"), along with a ballad, \"Ti i ja\" (\"You and I\"). In 2009, he released two singles, ''Hej ti'' (''Hey You''), which became a huge success, along with a ballad, \"Bez tebe\" (\"Without You\").\n\nHe played harmonica, then he started playing piano, synthesizers and other keyboards. He started writing songs for himself and for the other popular stars in [[ex-Yugoslavia]]. He was also a producer for the [[Montenegro|Montenegrin]] [[hip hop]] band [[Monteniggers]], and is still a friend with their only living member, [[Niggor]]. Georgiev and Niggor recorded the song \"Tropski bar\" together. He has his own record label, ''Barba Music'' and VG-Art studio production company, ''Studio Barba'', in Belgrade. He worked as coach in the two editions of the Serbian version of the talent-show ''The Voice'' (''Prvi glas Srbije'') in 2011\u201312.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n* ''Navika'' (''Habit''), 2001.\n* ''\u017dena bez imena'' (''Woman Without a Name''), 2003.\n* ''Daljina'' (''Distance''), 2013.\n\n===Singles===\n* ''[[Nisam ljubomoran]]'' (''I'm Not Jealous''), 2005.\n* ''Do svitanja'' (''Till Dawn''), 2007.\n* ''Hej ti'' (''Hey You''), 2009.\n* ''Tebe \u017eedan'' (''Thirsty Of You''), 2017.\n* ''Znam te najbolje'' (''I Know You The Best''), 2018.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Music of Serbia]]\n* [[List of people from Serbia#Music|List of singers from Serbia]]\n* [[Serbian pop]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.vladogeorgiev.com}}\n*